# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: lambda-type-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In computer programming, especially in functional programming and type theory, an **algebraic data type** (**ADT**) is a composite data type, i.e. a type formed by combining other types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] An algebraic data type is defined by two key constructions: a *sum* and a *product*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] These are sometimes referred to as "OR" and "AND" types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A **sum type** is a choice between possibilities.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The value of a sum type can match one of several defined *variants*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For example, a type representing the state of a traffic light could be either `Red`, `Amber`, or `Green`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A shape type could be either a `Circle` (which stores a radius) *or* a `Square` (which stores a width).
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In formal terms, these variants are known as tagged unions or disjoint unions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Each variant has a name, called a **constructor**, which can also carry data.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Enumerated types are a simple form of sum type where the constructors carry no data.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A **product type** combines types together.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A value of a product type will contain a value for each of its component types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For example, a `Point` type might be defined to contain an `x` coordinate (an integer) *and* a `y` coordinate (also an integer).
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Formal examples of product types include tuples and records.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The set of all possible values of a product type is the Cartesian product of the sets of its component types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Values of algebraic data types are typically handled using pattern matching.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] This feature allows a programmer to check which constructor a value was made with and extract the data it contains in a convenient and type-safe way.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types were introduced in Hope, a small functional programming language developed in the 1970s at the University of Edinburgh.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] One of the most common examples of an algebraic data type is the singly linked list.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A list type is a sum type with two variants, `Nil` for an empty list and `Cons *x* *xs*` for the combination of a new element *x* with a list *xs* to create a new list.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] `Cons` is an abbreviation of *cons*truct.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Many languages have special syntax for lists defined in this way.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For example, Haskell and ML use `[]` for `Nil`, `:` or `::` for `Cons`, respectively, and square brackets for entire lists.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Here, `Empty` represents an empty tree, `Leaf` represents a leaf node, and `Node` organizes the data into branches.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In most languages that support algebraic data types, it is possible to define parametric types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Examples are given later in this article.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Somewhat similar to a function, a data constructor is applied to arguments of an appropriate type, yielding an instance of the data type to which the type constructor belongs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For example, the data constructor `Leaf` is logically a function `Int -> Tree`, meaning that giving an integer as an argument to `Leaf` produces a value of the type `Tree`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] As `Node` takes two arguments of the type `Tree` itself, the datatype is recursive.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Operations on algebraic data types can be defined by using pattern matching to retrieve the arguments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Thus, a `Tree` given to `depth` can be constructed using any of `Empty`, `Leaf`, or `Node` and must be matched for any of them respectively to deal with all cases.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In case of `Node`, the pattern extracts the subtrees `l` and `r` for further processing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types are highly suited to implementing abstract syntax.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] An element of such a data type would have a form such as `Mult (Add (Number 4) (Minus (Number 0) (Number 1))) (Number 2)`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Writing an evaluation function for this language is a simple exercise; however, more complex transformations also become feasible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For example, an optimization pass in a compiler might be written as a function taking an abstract expression as input and returning an optimized form.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data types are used to represent values that can be one of several *types of things*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Each type of thing is associated with an identifier called a *constructor*, which can be considered a tag for that kind of data.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Each constructor can carry with it a different type of data.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For example, considering the binary `Tree` example shown above, a constructor could carry no data (e.g., `Empty`), or one piece of data (e.g., `Leaf` has one Int value), or multiple pieces of data (e.g., `Node` has one `Int` value and two `Tree` values).
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] To do something with a value of this `Tree` algebraic data type, it is *deconstructed* using a process called pattern matching.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] This involves matching the data with a series of *patterns*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The example function `depth` above pattern-matches its argument with three patterns.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] When the function is called, it finds the first pattern that matches its argument, performs any variable bindings that are found in the pattern, and evaluates the expression corresponding to the pattern.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Each pattern above has a form that resembles the structure of some possible value of this datatype.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The first pattern simply matches values of the constructor `Empty`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The second pattern matches values of the constructor `Leaf`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Patterns are recursive, so then the data that is associated with that constructor is matched with the pattern "n".
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In this case, a lowercase identifier represents a pattern that matches any value, which then is bound to a variable of that name — in this case, a variable "`n`" is bound to the integer value stored in the data type — to be used in the expression to evaluate.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Recursive patterns several layers deep are used for example in balancing red–black trees, which involve cases that require looking at colors several layers deep.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The advantages of algebraic data types can be highlighted by comparison of the above pseudocode with a pattern matching equivalent.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In the pseudocode example above, programmer diligence is required to not access field2 when the constructor is a `Leaf`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The type system would have difficulties assigning a static type in a safe way for traditional record data structures.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] However, in pattern matching such problems are not faced.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The type of each extracted value is based on the types declared by the relevant constructor.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The number of values that can be extracted is known based on the constructor.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Secondly, in pattern matching, the compiler performs exhaustiveness checking to ensure all cases are handled.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] If one of the cases of the *depth* function above were missing, the compiler would issue a warning.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Exhaustiveness checking may seem easy for simple patterns, but with many complex recursive patterns, the task soon becomes difficult for the average human (or compiler, if it must check arbitrary nested if-else constructs).
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Similarly, there may be patterns which never match (i.e., are already covered by prior patterns).
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The compiler can also check and issue warnings for these, as they may indicate an error in reasoning.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Algebraic data type pattern matching should not be confused with regular expression string pattern matching.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The purpose of both is similar (to extract parts from a piece of data matching certain constraints) however, the implementation is very different.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Pattern matching on algebraic data types matches on the structural properties of an object rather than on the character sequence of strings.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A general algebraic data type is a possibly recursive sum type of product types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Each constructor tags a product type to separate it from others, or if there is only one constructor, the data type is a product type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] Further, the parameter types of a constructor are the factors of the product type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] A parameterless constructor corresponds to the empty product.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] If a datatype is recursive, the entire sum of products is wrapped in a recursive type, and each constructor also rolls the datatype into the recursive type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] is represented in type theory as $\lambda \alpha .\mu \beta .1+\alpha \times \beta$ with constructors $\mathrm {nil} _{\alpha }=\mathrm {roll} \ (\mathrm {inl} \ \langle \rangle )$ and $\mathrm {cons} _{\alpha }\ x\ l=\mathrm {roll} \ (\mathrm {inr} \ \langle x,l\rangle )$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The Haskell List datatype can also be represented in type theory in a slightly different form, thus: $\mu \phi .\lambda \alpha .1+\alpha \times \phi \ \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] (Note how the $\mu$ and $\lambda$ constructs are reversed relative to the original.) The original formation specified a type function whose body was a recursive type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] The revised version specifies a recursive function on types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] (The type variable $\phi$ is used to suggest a function rather than a *base type* like $\beta$ , since $\phi$ is like a Greek *f*.) The function must also now be applied $\phi$ to its argument type $\alpha$ in the body of the type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] For the purposes of the List example, these two formulations are not significantly different; but the second form allows expressing so-called nested data types, i.e., those where the recursive type differs parametrically from the original.
[src:lambda-type-theory/algebraic-data-type] In set theory the equivalent of a sum type is a disjoint union, a set whose elements are pairs consisting of a tag (equivalent to a constructor) and an object of a type corresponding to the tag (equivalent to the constructor arguments).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In programming language theory and proof theory, the **Curry–Howard correspondence** is a direct relationship between computer programs and mathematical proofs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] It is also known as the **Curry–Howard isomorphism** or **equivalence**, or the **proofs-as-programs** and **propositions-** or **formulae-as-types interpretation**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] It is a generalization of a syntactic analogy between systems of formal logic and computational calculi that was first discovered by the American mathematician Haskell Curry and the logician William Alvin Howard.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] It is the link between logic and computation that is usually attributed to Curry and Howard, although the idea is related to the operational interpretation of intuitionistic logic given in various formulations by L.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Brouwer, Arend Heyting and Andrey Kolmogorov (see Brouwer–Heyting–Kolmogorov interpretation) and Stephen Kleene (see Realizability).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The relationship has been extended to include category theory as the three-way **Curry–Howard–Lambek correspondence**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In 1958, he observes that a certain kind of proof system, referred to as Hilbert-style deduction systems, coincides on some fragment with the typed fragment of a standard model of computation known as combinatory logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In 1969 Howard observes that another, more "high-level" proof system, referred to as natural deduction, can be directly interpreted in its intuitionistic version as a typed variant of the model of computation known as lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Actually, Howard's first formulation of the isomorphism was referred to (a variant of) Gentzen's sequent calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The observation that the isomorphism is best understood with natural deduction, as well as the current formulation of the isomorphism itself, are due to Per Martin-Löf.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The Curry–Howard correspondence is the observation that there is an isomorphism between the proof systems, and the models of computation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] It is the statement that these two families of formalisms can be considered as identical.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] If one abstracts on the peculiarities of either formalism, the following generalization arises: *a proof is a program, and the formula it proves is the type for the program*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This sets a form of logic programming on a rigorous foundation: *proofs can be represented as programs, and especially as lambda terms*, or *proofs can be **run***.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The correspondence has been the starting point of a large range of new research after its discovery, leading to a new class of formal systems designed to act both as a proof system and as a typed programming language based on functional programming.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This includes Martin-Löf's intuitionistic type theory and Coquand's calculus of constructions (CoC), two calculi in which proofs are regular objects of the discourse and in which one can state properties of proofs the same way as of any program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This field of research is usually referred to as modern type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Such typed lambda calculi derived from the Curry–Howard paradigm led to software like Rocq in which proofs seen as programs can be formalized, checked, and run.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] A converse direction is to *use a program to extract a proof*, given its correctness, an area of research closely related to proof-carrying code.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This is only feasible if the programming language the program is written for is very richly typed: the development of such type systems has been partly motivated by the wish to make the Curry–Howard correspondence practically relevant.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The Curry–Howard correspondence also raised new questions regarding the computational content of proof concepts that were not covered by the original works of Curry and Howard.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In particular, classical logic has been shown to correspond to the ability to manipulate the continuation of programs and the symmetry of sequent calculus to express the duality between the two evaluation strategies known as call-by-name and call-by-value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Because of the possibility of writing non-terminating programs, Turing-complete models of computation (such as languages with arbitrary recursive functions) must be interpreted with care, as naive application of the correspondence leads to an inconsistent logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] A more radical approach, advocated by total functional programming, is to eliminate unrestricted recursion (and forgo Turing completeness, although still retaining high computational complexity), using more controlled corecursion wherever non-terminating behavior is actually desired.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In its more general formulation, the Curry–Howard correspondence is a correspondence between formal proof calculi and type systems for models of computation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In particular, it splits into two correspondences.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] One at the level of formulas and types that is independent of which particular proof system or model of computation is considered, and one at the level of proofs and programs which, this time, is specific to the particular choice of proof system and model of computation considered.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Quantifiers correspond to dependent function space or products (as appropriate).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] For this reason, these schemes are now often called axioms K and S.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Examples of programs seen as proofs in a Hilbert-style logic are given below.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] If one restricts to the implicational intuitionistic fragment, a simple way to formalize logic in Hilbert's style is as follows.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Let Γ be a finite collection of formulas, considered as hypotheses.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This can be formalized using inference rules, as in the left column of the following table.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Typed combinatory logic can be formulated using a similar syntax: let Γ be a finite collection of variables, annotated with their types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The generation rules defined here are given in the right-column below.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Curry's remark simply states that both columns are in one-to-one correspondence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The restriction of the correspondence to intuitionistic logic means that some classical tautologies, such as Peirce's law ((*α* → *β*) → *α*) → *α*, are excluded from the correspondence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Seen at a more abstract level, the correspondence can be restated as shown in the following table.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Especially, the deduction theorem specific to Hilbert-style logic matches the process of abstraction elimination of combinatory logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Thanks to the correspondence, results from combinatory logic can be transferred to Hilbert-style logic and vice versa.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] For instance, the notion of reduction of terms in combinatory logic can be transferred to Hilbert-style logic and it provides a way to canonically transform proofs into other proofs of the same statement.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] One can also transfer the notion of normal terms to a notion of normal proofs, expressing that the hypotheses of the axioms never need to be all detached (since otherwise a simplification can happen).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Results on the completeness of some sets of combinators or axioms can also be transferred.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] After Curry emphasized the syntactic correspondence between intuitionistic Hilbert-style deduction and typed combinatory logic, Howard made explicit in 1969 a syntactic analogy between the programs of simply typed lambda calculus and the proofs of natural deduction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In the left-hand side, Γ, Γ1 and Γ2 denote ordered sequences of formulas while in the right-hand side, they denote sequences of named (i.e., typed) formulas with all names different.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] To paraphrase the correspondence, proving Γ ⊢ *α* means having a program that, given values with the types listed in Γ, manufactures an object of type *α*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] An axiom/hypothesis corresponds to the introduction of a new variable with a new, unconstrained type, the → *I* rule corresponds to function abstraction and the → *E* rule corresponds to function application.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Observe that the correspondence is not exact if the context Γ is taken to be a set of formulas as, e.g., the λ-terms λ*x*.λ*y*.*x* and λ*x*.λ*y*.*y* of type *α* → *α* → *α* would not be distinguished in the correspondence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Howard showed that the correspondence extends to other connectives of the logic and other constructions of simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Seen at an abstract level, the correspondence can then be summarized as shown in the following table.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Especially, it also shows that the notion of normal forms in lambda calculus matches Prawitz's notion of normal deduction in natural deduction, from which it follows that the algorithms for the type inhabitation problem can be turned into algorithms for deciding intuitionistic provability.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Howard's correspondence naturally extends to other extensions of natural deduction and simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] At the time of Curry, and also at the time of Howard, the proofs-as-programs correspondence concerned only intuitionistic logic, i.e. a logic in which, in particular, Peirce's law was *not* deducible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The extension of the correspondence to Peirce's law and hence to classical logic became clear from the work of Griffin on typing operators that capture the evaluation context of a given program execution so that this evaluation context can be later on reinstalled.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The basic Curry–Howard-style correspondence for classical logic is given below.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Note the correspondence between the double-negation translation used to map classical proofs to intuitionistic logic and the continuation-passing-style translation used to map lambda terms involving control to pure lambda terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] More particularly, call-by-name continuation-passing-style translations relates to Kolmogorov's double negation translation and call-by-value continuation-passing-style translations relates to a kind of double-negation translation due to Kuroda.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] A finer Curry–Howard correspondence exists for classical logic if one defines classical logic not by adding an axiom such as Peirce's law, but by allowing several conclusions in sequents.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In the case of classical natural deduction, there exists a proofs-as-programs correspondence with the typed programs of Parigot's λμ-calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] A proofs-as-programs correspondence can be settled for the formalism known as Gentzen's sequent calculus but it is not a correspondence with a well-defined pre-existing model of computation as it was for Hilbert-style and natural deductions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Sequent calculus is characterized by the presence of left introduction rules, right introduction rule and a cut rule that can be eliminated.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The structure of sequent calculus relates to a calculus whose structure is close to the one of some abstract machines.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Although Prawitz's homomorphism is less powerful than the Curry-Howard isomorphism, with a stronger type-language it becomes an isomorphism too, though still missing dependent types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Prawitz was presumably unaware of Howard's work, especially since the talk from which his 1970 paper is drawn was delivered one year before Howard's manuscript started circulating.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] G. de Bruijn used the lambda notation for representing proofs of the theorem checker Automath, and represented propositions as "categories" of their proofs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] It was in the late 1960s at the same period of time Howard wrote his manuscript; de Bruijn was likely unaware of Howard's work, and stated the correspondence independently.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Some researchers tend to use the term Curry–Howard–de Bruijn correspondence in place of Curry–Howard correspondence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The BHK interpretation interprets intuitionistic proofs as functions but it does not specify the class of functions relevant for the interpretation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] If one takes lambda calculus for this class of function, then the BHK interpretation tells the same as Howard's correspondence between natural deduction and lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Kreisel's modified realizability applies to intuitionistic higher-order predicate logic and shows that the simply typed lambda term inductively extracted from the proof realizes the initial formula.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In the case of propositional logic, it coincides with Howard's statement: the extracted lambda term is the proof itself (seen as an untyped lambda term) and the realizability statement is a paraphrase of the fact that the extracted lambda term has the type that the formula means (seen as a type).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Gödel's dialectica interpretation realizes (an extension of) intuitionistic arithmetic with computable functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The connection with lambda calculus is unclear, even in the case of natural deduction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Joachim Lambek showed in the early 1970s that the proofs of intuitionistic propositional logic and the combinators of typed combinatory logic share a common equational theory, the theory of cartesian closed categories.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The expression Curry–Howard–Lambek correspondence is now used by some people to refer to the relationships between intuitionistic logic, typed lambda calculus and cartesian closed categories.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Under this correspondence, objects of a cartesian-closed category can be interpreted as propositions (types), and morphisms as deductions mapping a set of assumptions (typing context) to a valid consequent (well-typed term).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] For example, it is not possible to state or prove that a morphism is normalizing, establish a Church-Rosser type theorem, or speak of a "strongly normalizing" cartesian closed category.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] To clarify this distinction, the underlying syntactic structure of cartesian closed categories is rephrased below.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Equivalently to the annotations above, well-defined morphisms (typed terms) in any cartesian-closed category can be constructed according to the following typing rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The usual categorical morphism notation $f:\alpha \to \beta$ is replaced with typing context notation $\alpha \vdash f:\beta$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Now, there exists t such that $\alpha _{1}\times \ldots \times \alpha _{n}\vdash t:\beta$ iff $\alpha _{1},\ldots ,\alpha _{n}\vdash \beta$ is provable in implicational intuitionistic logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Thanks to the Curry–Howard correspondence, a typed expression whose type corresponds to a logical formula is analogous to a proof of that formula.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] As an example, consider a proof of the theorem *α* → *α*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] In lambda calculus, this is the type of the identity function **I** = *λx*.*x* and in combinatory logic, the identity function is obtained by applying **S** = *λfgx*.*fx*(*gx*) twice to **K** = *λxy*.*x*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Since *P* is being applied to *Q*, the type of *P* must have the form *α* → *β* and the type of *Q* must have the form α for some α and β.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Therefore, it is possible to detach the conclusion, β, via the modus ponens rule.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] As a more complicated example, let's look at the theorem that corresponds to the **B** function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This is our roadmap for the proof of the theorem (*β* → *α*) → (*γ* → *β*) → *γ* → *α*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The first step is to construct (**K** **S**).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This is the theorem that corresponds to the type of (**K** **S**).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] This last formula must be applied to **K**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The diagram below gives proof of (*β* → *α*) → (*γ* → *β*) → *γ* → *α* in natural deduction and shows how it can be interpreted as the λ-expression λ*a*.λ*b*.λ*g*.(*a* (*b* *g*)) of type (*β* → *α*) → (*γ* → *β*) → *γ* → *α*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Recently, the isomorphism has been proposed as a way to define search space partition in genetic programming.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The method indexes sets of genotypes (the program trees evolved by the GP system) by their Curry–Howard isomorphic proof (referred to as a species).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] As noted by INRIA research director Bernard Lang, the Curry-Howard correspondence constitutes an argument against the patentability of software: since algorithms are mathematical proofs, patentability of the former would imply patentability of the latter.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] A theorem could be private property; a mathematician would have to pay for using it, and to trust the company that sells it but keeps its proof secret and rejects responsibility for any errors.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The correspondences listed here go much farther and deeper.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] For example, cartesian closed categories are generalized by closed monoidal categories.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] The internal language of these categories is the linear type system (corresponding to linear logic), which generalizes simply-typed lambda calculus as the internal language of cartesian closed categories.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Moreover, these can be shown to correspond to cobordisms, which play a vital role in string theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] An extended set of equivalences is also explored in homotopy type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] Here, type theory is extended by the univalence axiom ("equivalence is equivalent to equality") which permits homotopy type theory to be used as a foundation for all of mathematics (including set theory and classical logic, providing new ways to discuss the axiom of choice and many other things).
[src:lambda-type-theory/curry-howard-correspondence] That is, the Curry–Howard correspondence that proofs are elements of inhabited types is generalized to the notion of homotopic equivalence of proofs (as paths in space, the identity type or equality type of type theory being interpreted as a path).
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In computer science and logic, a **dependent type** is a type whose definition depends on a value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] It is an overlapping feature of type theory and type systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In intuitionistic type theory, dependent types are used to encode logic's quantifiers like "for all" and "there exists".
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In functional programming languages like Agda, ATS, Rocq (previously known as *Coq*), F*, Epigram, Idris, and Lean, dependent types help reduce bugs by enabling the programmer to assign types that further restrain the set of possible implementations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Two common examples of dependent types are *dependent functions* and *dependent pairs*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The return type of a dependent function may depend on the *value* (not just type) of one of its arguments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] For instance, a function that takes a positive integer n may return an array of length n , where the array length is part of the type of the array.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] (Note that this is different from polymorphism and generic programming, both of which include the type as an argument.) A dependent pair may have a second value, the type of which depends on the first value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Sticking with the array example, a dependent pair may be used to pair an array with its length in a type-safe way.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Dependent types add complexity to a type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Deciding the equality of dependent types in a program may require computations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In 1934, Haskell Curry noticed that the types used in typed lambda calculus, and in its combinatory logic counterpart, followed the same pattern as axioms in propositional logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Going further, for every proof in the logic, there was a matching function (term) in the programming language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] One of Curry's examples was the correspondence between simply typed lambda calculus and intuitionistic logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Predicate logic is an extension of propositional logic, adding quantifiers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Howard and de Bruijn extended lambda calculus to match this more powerful logic by creating types for dependent functions, which correspond to "for all", and dependent pairs, which correspond to "there exists".
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Because of this, and other work by Howard, propositions-as-types is known as the Curry–Howard correspondence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In dependent type theory, a dependent type is a type whose specification may vary with a value, and can be viewed as analogous to an indexed family of sets.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Let ${\mathcal {U}}$ denote a universe of types, and write $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ to indicate that A is a type in ${\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] A dependent **family of types** over A is written $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , meaning that to each term $a:A$ the family assigns a type $B(a):{\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Thus, given $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , the expression $B(a)$ denotes a type that depends on the particular value a .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In standard terminology, this is described by saying that the type $B(a)$ varies with a .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] A function whose type of return value varies with its argument (i.e. there is no fixed codomain) is a **dependent function** and the type of this function is called **dependent product type**, **pi-type** (**Π type**) or **dependent function type**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] From a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ we may construct the type of dependent functions ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ , whose terms are functions that take a term $a:A$ and return a term in $B(a)$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] For this example, the dependent function type is typically written as ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B(x)}$ or ${\textstyle \prod {(x:A)}B(x)}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] If $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ is a constant function, the corresponding dependent product type is equivalent to an ordinary function type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] That is, ${\textstyle \prod _{x:A}B}$ is judgmentally equal to $A\to B$ when B does not depend on x .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The name 'Π-type' comes from the idea that these may be viewed as a Cartesian product of types. Π-types can also be understood as models of universal quantifiers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] For example, if we write $\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)$ for *n*-tuples of real numbers, then ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }\operatorname {Vec} (\mathbb {R} ,n)}$ would be the type of a function which, given a natural number n, returns a tuple of real numbers of size n.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The usual function space arises as a special case when the range type does not actually depend on the input.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] E.g. ${\textstyle \prod _{n:\mathbb {N} }{\mathbb {R} }}$ is the type of functions from natural numbers to the real numbers, which is written as $\mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {R}$ in typed lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The dual of the dependent product type is the **dependent pair type**, **dependent sum type**, **sigma-type**, or (confusingly) **dependent product type**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Sigma-types can also be understood as existential quantifiers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Continuing the above example, if, in the universe of types ${\mathcal {U}}$ , there is a type $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ and a family of types $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ , then there is a dependent pair type ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The dependent pair type captures the idea of an ordered pair where the type of the second term is dependent on the value of the first.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] If B is a constant function, then the dependent pair type becomes (is judgmentally equal to) the product type, that is, an ordinary Cartesian product $A\times B$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] For a more concrete example, taking A to again be type of unsigned integers from 0 to 255, and $B(a)$ to again be equal to $X_{a}$ for 256 more arbitrary $X_{a}$ , then ${\textstyle \sum _{x:A}B(x)}$ devolves into the sum $X_{0}+X_{1}+X_{2}+\ldots +X_{253}+X_{254}+X_{255}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Let $A:{\mathcal {U}}$ be some type, and let $B:A\to {\mathcal {U}}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] By the Curry–Howard correspondence, B can be interpreted as a logical predicate on terms of A .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] For a given $a:A$ , whether the type $B(a)$ is inhabited indicates whether a satisfies this predicate.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The correspondence can be extended to existential quantification and dependent pairs: the proposition $\exists {a}{\in }A\,B(a)$ is true if and only if the type ${\textstyle \sum _{a:A}B(a)}$ is inhabited.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] For example, $m:\mathbb {N}$ is less than or equal to $n:\mathbb {N}$ if and only if there exists another natural number $k:\mathbb {N}$ such that $m+k=n$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] That is, a proof of the statement that m is less than or equal to n is a pair that contains both a non-negative number k , which is the difference between m and n , and a proof of the equality $m+k=n$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] Henk Barendregt developed the lambda cube as a means of classifying type systems along three axes.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The eight corners of the resulting cube-shaped diagram each correspond to a type system, with simply typed lambda calculus in the least expressive corner, and calculus of constructions in the most expressive.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The three axes of the cube correspond to three different augmentations of the simply typed lambda calculus: the addition of dependent types, the addition of polymorphism, and the addition of higher kinded type constructors (functions from types to types, for example).
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The lambda cube is generalized further by pure type systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi$ of pure first order dependent types, corresponding to the logical framework LF, is obtained by generalising the function space type of the simply typed lambda calculus to the dependent product type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The system $\lambda \Pi 2$ of second order dependent types is obtained from $\lambda \Pi$ by allowing quantification over type constructors.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] In this theory the dependent product operator subsumes both the $\to$ operator of simply typed lambda calculus and the $\forall$ binder of System F.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The higher order system $\lambda \Pi \omega$ extends $\lambda \Pi 2$ to all four forms of abstraction from the lambda cube: functions from terms to terms, types to types, terms to types and types to terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The system corresponds to the calculus of constructions whose derivative, the calculus of inductive constructions is the underlying system of Rocq.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The Curry–Howard correspondence implies that types can be constructed that express arbitrarily complex mathematical properties.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] If the user can supply a constructive proof that a type is *inhabited* (i.e., that a value of that type exists) then a compiler can check the proof and convert it into executable computer code that computes the value by carrying out the construction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The proof checking feature makes dependently typed languages closely related to proof assistants.
[src:lambda-type-theory/dependent-type] The code-generation aspect provides a powerful approach to formal program verification and proof-carrying code, since the code is derived directly from a mechanically verified mathematical proof.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] A **Hindley–Milner** (**HM**) **type system** is a classical type system for the lambda calculus with parametric polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] It is also known as **Damas–Milner** or **Damas–Hindley–Milner**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Roger Hindley and later rediscovered by Robin Milner.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Luis Damas contributed a close formal analysis and proof of the method in his PhD thesis.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Among HM's more notable properties are its completeness and its ability to infer the most general type of a given program without programmer-supplied type annotations or other hints.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Algorithm W is an efficient type inference method in practice and has been successfully applied on large code bases, although it has a high theoretical complexity.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] HM is preferably used for functional programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] It was first implemented as part of the type system of the programming language ML.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Since then, HM has been extended in various ways, most notably with type class constraints like those in Haskell.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] As a type inference method, Hindley–Milner is able to deduce the types of variables, expressions and functions from programs written in an entirely untyped style.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Being scope sensitive, it is not limited to deriving the types only from a small portion of source code, but rather from complete programs or modules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Being able to cope with parametric types, too, it is core to the type systems of many functional programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] It was first applied in this manner in the ML programming language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The origin is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Roger Hindley extended this work and proved that their algorithm always inferred the most general type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] In 1978, Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] In 1982, Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] In the simply typed lambda calculus, types T are either atomic type constants or function types of form T → T {\displaystyle T\rightarrow T} ({\displaystyle T\rightarrow T}).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Contrary to this, the untyped lambda calculus is neutral to typing at all, and many of its functions can be meaningfully applied to all type of arguments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] which simply returns whatever value it is applied to.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Less trivial examples include parametric types like lists.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] While polymorphism in general means that operations accept values of more than one type, the polymorphism used here is parametric.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] One finds the notation of *type schemes* in the literature, too, emphasizing the parametric nature of the polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Additionally, constants may be typed with (quantified) type variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Polymorphic types can become monomorphic by consistent substitution of their variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] More generally, types are polymorphic when they contain type variables, while types without them are monomorphic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Contrary to the type systems used for example in Pascal (1970) or C (1972), which only support monomorphic types, HM is designed with emphasis on parametric polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The successors of the languages mentioned, like C++ (1985), focused on different types of polymorphism, namely subtyping in connection with object-oriented programming and overloading.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] While subtyping is incompatible with HM, a variant of systematic overloading is available in the HM-based type system of Haskell.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] When extending the type inference for the simply-typed lambda calculus towards polymorphism, one has to decide whether assigning a polymorphic type not only as type of an expression, but also as the type of a λ-bound variable is admissible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Allowing this gives rise to the polymorphic lambda calculus; however, type inference in this system is not decidable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Instead, HM distinguishes variables that are immediately bound to an expression from more general λ-bound variables, calling the former let-bound variables, and allows polymorphic types to be assigned only to these.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] which can be typed with a polymorphic type for 'id'.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] As indicated, the expression syntax is extended to make the let-bound variables explicit, and by restricting the type system to allow only let-bound variable to have polymorphic types, while the parameters in lambda-abstractions must get a monomorphic type, type inference becomes decidable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The same description of the deduction system is used throughout, even for the two algorithms, to make the various forms in which the HM method is presented directly comparable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The type system can be formally described by syntax rules that fix a language for the expressions, types, etc.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The presentation here of such a syntax is not too formal, in that it is written down not to study the surface grammar, but rather the depth grammar, and leaves some syntactical details open.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Building on this, typing rules are used to define how expressions and types are related.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] As before, the form used is a bit liberal.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The expressions to be typed are exactly those of the lambda calculus extended with a let-expression as shown in the adjacent table.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Parentheses can be used to disambiguate an expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The application is left-binding and binds stronger than abstraction or the let-in construct.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Types are syntactically split into two groups, monotypes and polytypes.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Monotypes always designate a particular type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Monotypes τ {\displaystyle \tau } ({\displaystyle \tau }) are syntactically represented as terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The complete set of type functions C {\displaystyle C} ({\displaystyle C}) is arbitrary in HM, except that it *must* contain at least → 2 {\displaystyle \rightarrow ^{2}} ({\displaystyle \rightarrow ^{2}}), the type of functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] It is often written in infix notation for convenience.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] For example, a function mapping integers to strings has type i n t → s t r i n g {\displaystyle {\mathtt {int}}\rightarrow {\mathtt {string}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathtt {int}}\rightarrow {\mathtt {string}}}).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Again, parentheses can be used to disambiguate a type expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The application binds stronger than the infix arrow, which is right-binding.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Type variables are admitted as monotypes.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Monotypes are not to be confused with monomorphic types, which exclude variables and allow only ground terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Two monotypes are equal if they have identical terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] A function with polytype ∀ α . α → α {\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha } ({\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha }) can map *any* value of the same type to itself, and the identity function is a value for this type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] ( S e t α ) → i n t {\displaystyle \forall \alpha .({\mathtt {Set}}\ \alpha )\rightarrow {\mathtt {int}}} ({\displaystyle \forall \alpha .({\mathtt {Set}}\ \alpha )\rightarrow {\mathtt {int}}}) is the type of a function mapping all finite sets to integers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] A function which returns the cardinality of a set would be a value of this type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] For instance, a type ∀ α . α → ∀ α . α {\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \forall \alpha .\alpha } ({\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \forall \alpha .\alpha }) is excluded by the syntax of types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Equality of polytypes is up to reordering the quantification and renaming the quantified variables ( α {\displaystyle \alpha } ({\displaystyle \alpha })-conversion).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Further, quantified variables not occurring in the monotype can be dropped.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] To meaningfully bring together the still disjoint parts (syntax expressions and types) a third part is needed: context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Additionally to the quantification ∀ {\displaystyle \forall } ({\displaystyle \forall }) in polytypes, type variables can also be bound by occurring in the context, but with the inverse effect on the right hand side of the ⊢ {\displaystyle \vdash } ({\displaystyle \vdash }).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Such variables then behave like type constants there.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Finally, a type variable may legally occur unbound in a typing, in which case they are implicitly all-quantified.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The presence of both bound and unbound type variables is a bit uncommon in programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Often, all type variables are implicitly treated all-quantified.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] For instance, one does not have clauses with free variables in Prolog.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Likewise in Haskell, where all type variables implicitly occur quantified, i.e. a Haskell type `a -> a` means ∀ α . α → α {\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha } ({\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha }) here.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Related and also very uncommon is the binding effect of the right hand side σ {\displaystyle \sigma } ({\displaystyle \sigma }) of the assignments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Typically, the mixture of both bound and unbound type variables originate from the use of free variables in an expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The constant function **K** = λ x . λ y . x {\displaystyle \lambda x.\lambda y.x} ({\displaystyle \lambda x.\lambda y.x}) provides an example.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] It has the monotype α → β → α {\displaystyle \alpha \rightarrow \beta \rightarrow \alpha } ({\displaystyle \alpha \rightarrow \beta \rightarrow \alpha }).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] One can force polymorphism by l e t k = λ x .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] ( l e t f = λ y . x i n f ) i n k {\displaystyle \mathbf {let} \ k=\lambda x.(\mathbf {let} \ f=\lambda y.x\ \mathbf {in} \ f)\ \mathbf {in} \ k} ({\displaystyle \mathbf {let} \ k=\lambda x.(\mathbf {let} \ f=\lambda y.x\ \mathbf {in} \ f)\ \mathbf {in} \ k}).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Herein, f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) has the type ∀ γ . γ → α {\displaystyle \forall \gamma .\gamma \rightarrow \alpha } ({\displaystyle \forall \gamma .\gamma \rightarrow \alpha }).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] One could imagine the free type variable α {\displaystyle \alpha } ({\displaystyle \alpha }) in the type of f {\displaystyle f} ({\displaystyle f}) be bound by the ∀ α {\displaystyle \forall \alpha } ({\displaystyle \forall \alpha }) in the type of k {\displaystyle k} ({\displaystyle k}).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] But such a scoping cannot be expressed in HM.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Rather, the binding is realized by the context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Polymorphism means that one and the same expression can have (perhaps infinitely) many types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] But in this type system, these types are not completely unrelated, but rather orchestrated by the parametric polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The counter-example fails because the replacement is not consistent.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] As the example suggests, substitution is not only strongly related to an order, that expresses that a type is more or less special, but also with the all-quantification which allows the substitution to be applied.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] This order is part of the type definition of the type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] While substituting a monomorphic (ground) type for a quantified variable is straight forward, substituting a polytype has some pitfalls caused by the presence of free variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Most particularly, unbound variables must not be replaced.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Additionally, quantifications can only occur top-level.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Substituting a parametric type, one has to lift its quantifiers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The table on the right makes the rule precise.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Alternatively, consider an equivalent notation for the polytypes without quantifiers in which quantified variables are represented by a different set of symbols.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] In such a notation, the specialization reduces to plain consistent replacement of such variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The relation ⊑ {\displaystyle \sqsubseteq } ({\displaystyle \sqsubseteq }) is a partial order and ∀ α . α {\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha } ({\displaystyle \forall \alpha .\alpha }) is its smallest element.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] While specialization of a type scheme is one use of the order, it plays a crucial second role in the type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Type inference with polymorphism faces the challenge of summarizing all possible types an expression may have.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The order guarantees that such a summary exists as the most general type of the expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Contrary to the specialisation rule, this is not part of the definition, but like the implicit all-quantification rather a consequence of the type rules defined next.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Free type variables in a typing serve as placeholders for possible refinement.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The binding effect of the environment to free type variables on the right hand side of ⊢ {\displaystyle \vdash } ({\displaystyle \vdash }) that prohibits their substitution in the specialisation rule is again that a replacement has to be consistent and would need to include the whole typing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The syntax of HM is carried forward to the syntax of the inference rules that form the body of the formal system, by using the typings as judgments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Each of the rules define what conclusion could be drawn from what premises.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Additionally to the judgments, some extra conditions introduced above might be used as premises, too.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] A proof using the rules is a sequence of judgments such that all premises are listed before a conclusion.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The examples below show a possible format of proofs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] From left to right, each line shows the conclusion, the [ N a m e ] {\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Name}}]} ({\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Name}}]}) of the rule applied and the premises, either by referring to an earlier line (number) if the premise is a judgment or by making the predicate explicit.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The side box shows the deduction rules of the HM type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Their meaning is obvious at the first glance, as they decompose each expression, prove their sub-expressions and finally combine the individual types found in the premises to the type in the conclusion.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The second group is formed by the remaining two rules [ I n s t ] {\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Inst}}]} ({\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Inst}}]}) and [ G e n ] {\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Gen}}]} ({\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Gen}}]}).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] They handle specialization and generalization of types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] While the rule [ I n s t ] {\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Inst}}]} ({\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Inst}}]}) should be clear from the section on specialization above, [ G e n ] {\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Gen}}]} ({\displaystyle [{\mathtt {Gen}}]}) complements the former, working in the opposite direction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] It allows generalization, i.e. to quantify monotype variables not bound in the context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The following two examples exercise the rule system in action.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Since both the expression and the type are given, they are a type-checking use of the rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Remember that σ {\displaystyle \sigma } ({\displaystyle \sigma }) and τ {\displaystyle \tau } ({\displaystyle \tau }) denote poly- and monotypes respectively.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] As a consequence of this regulation, λ f .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The generalisation rule is also worth a closer look.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] This is possible, since α {\displaystyle \alpha } ({\displaystyle \alpha }) does not occur free in the context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Again, while this makes the generalization rule plausible, it is not really a consequence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] On the contrary, the generalization rule is part of the definition of HM's type system and the implicit all-quantification a consequence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Now that the deduction system of HM is at hand, one could present an algorithm and validate it with respect to the rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Alternatively, it might be possible to derive it by taking a closer look on how the rules interact and proof are formed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] This is done in the remainder of this article focusing on the possible decisions one can make while proving a typing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Such a chain could also exist between the conclusion of the proof and the rule for topmost expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] All proofs must have the so sketched shape.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] This is in fact possible and leads to a variant of the rules system with no such rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] A contemporary treatment of HM uses a purely syntax-directed rule system due to Clement as an intermediate step.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] implying, one can derive the principal type for an expression in ⊢ S {\displaystyle \vdash _{S}} ({\displaystyle \vdash _{S}}) allowing us to generalize the proof in the end.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Comparing ⊢ D {\displaystyle \vdash _{D}} ({\displaystyle \vdash _{D}}) and ⊢ S {\displaystyle \vdash _{S}} ({\displaystyle \vdash _{S}}), now only monotypes appear in the judgments of all rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Additionally, the shape of any possible proof with the deduction system is now identical to the shape of the expression (both seen as trees).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Thus the expression fully determines the shape of the proof.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Now that the shape of the proof is known, one is already close to formulating a type inference algorithm.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Because any proof for a given expression must have the same shape, one can assume the monotypes in the proof's judgements to be undetermined and consider how to determine them.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Here, the substitution (specialisation) order comes into play.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The second premise requires that the inferred type is equal to τ of the first premise.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Now there are two possibly different types, perhaps with open type variables, at hand to compare and to make equal if it is possible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] If it is, a refinement is found, and if not, a type error is detected again.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] An effective method is known to "make two terms equal" by substitution, Robinson's Unification in combination with the so-called Union-Find algorithm.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] To briefly summarize the union-find algorithm, given the set of all types in a proof, it allows one to group them together into equivalence classes by means of a union procedure and to pick a representative for each such class using a find procedure.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Emphasizing the word procedure in the sense of side effect, we're clearly leaving the realm of logic in order to prepare an effective algorithm.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Now having a sketch of an inference algorithm at hand, a more formal presentation is given in the next section.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The presentation of Algorithm J is a misuse of the notation of logical rules, since it includes side effects but allows a direct comparison with ⊢ S {\displaystyle \vdash _{S}} ({\displaystyle \vdash _{S}}) while expressing an efficient implementation at the same time.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The rules now specify a procedure with parameters Γ , e {\displaystyle \Gamma ,e} ({\displaystyle \Gamma ,e}) yielding τ {\displaystyle \tau } ({\displaystyle \tau }) in the conclusion where the execution of the premises proceeds from left to right.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] The procedure i n s t ( σ ) {\displaystyle inst(\sigma )} ({\displaystyle inst(\sigma )}) specializes the polytype σ {\displaystyle \sigma } ({\displaystyle \sigma }) by copying the term and replacing the bound type variables consistently by new monotype variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] ' n e w v a r {\displaystyle newvar} ({\displaystyle newvar})' produces a new monotype variable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Likely, Γ ¯ ( τ ) {\displaystyle {\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )} ({\displaystyle {\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )}) has to copy the type introducing new variables for the quantification to avoid unwanted captures.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Overall, the algorithm now proceeds by always making the most general choice leaving the specialization to the unification, which by itself produces the most general result.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] As noted above, the final result τ {\displaystyle \tau } ({\displaystyle \tau }) has to be generalized to Γ ¯ ( τ ) {\displaystyle {\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )} ({\displaystyle {\bar {\Gamma }}(\tau )}) in the end, to gain the most general type for a given expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Because the procedures used in the algorithm have nearly O(1) cost, the overall cost of the algorithm is close to linear in the size of the expression for which a type is to be inferred.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] This is in strong contrast to many other attempts to derive type inference algorithms, which often came out to be NP-hard, if not undecidable with respect to termination.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Thus the HM performs as well as the best fully informed type-checking algorithms can.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Type-checking here means that an algorithm does not have to find a proof, but only to validate a given one.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] ( x x ) {\displaystyle \lambda \ x.(x\ x)} ({\displaystyle \lambda \ x.(x\ x)}), for which no type can be derived using HM.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Practically, types are only small terms and do not build up expanding structures.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p01] Thus, in complexity analysis, one can treat comparing them as a constant, retaining O(1) costs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] In the previous section, while sketching the algorithm its proof was hinted at with metalogical argumentation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While this leads to an efficient algorithm J, it is not clear whether the algorithm properly reflects the deduction systems D or S which serve as a semantic base line.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The most critical point in the above argumentation is the refinement of monotype variables bound by the context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] For instance, the algorithm boldly changes the context while inferring e.g. λ f .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The problem is that the deduction rules do not allow such a refinement.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Arguing that the refined type could have been added earlier instead of the monotype variable is an expedient at best.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The key to reaching a formally satisfying argument is to properly include the context within the refinement.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Formally, typing is compatible with substitution of free type variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] To refine the free variables thus means to refine the whole typing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The presentation of algorithm W in the sidebar still makes use of side effects in the operations set in italic, but these are now limited to generating fresh symbols.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While algorithm W is normally considered to be *the* HM algorithm and is often directly presented after the rule system in literature, its purpose is described by Milner on P.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] As it stands, W is hardly an efficient algorithm; substitutions are applied too often.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] It was formulated to aid the proof of soundness.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] We now present a simpler algorithm J which simulates W in a precise sense.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While he considered W more complicated and less efficient, he presented it in his publication before J.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] It has its merits when side effects are unavailable or unwanted.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] W is also needed to prove completeness, which is factored by him into the soundness proof.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Before formulating the proof obligations, a deviation between the rules systems D and S and the algorithms presented needs to be emphasized.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While the development above sort of misused the monotypes as "open" proof variables, the possibility that proper monotype variables might be harmed was sidestepped by introducing fresh variables and hoping for the best.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] But there's a catch: One of the promises made was that these fresh variables would be "kept in mind" as such.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] This promise is not fulfilled by the algorithm.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] This omission can easily be fixed by more carefully distinguishing proof variables and monotype variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The authors were well aware of the problem but decided not to fix it.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] One might assume a pragmatic reason behind this.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While more properly implementing the type inference would have enabled the algorithm to deal with abstract monotypes, they were not needed for the intended application where none of the items in a preexisting context have free variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] In this light, the unneeded complication was dropped in favor of a simpler algorithm.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The remaining downside is that the proof of the algorithm with respect to the rule system is less general and can only be made for contexts with f r e e ( Γ ) = ∅ {\displaystyle free(\Gamma )=\emptyset } ({\displaystyle free(\Gamma )=\emptyset }) as a side condition.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The side condition in the completeness obligation addresses how the deduction may give many types, while the algorithm always produces one.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] At the same time, the side condition demands that the type inferred is actually the most general.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] From there, the proofs are by induction over the expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Another proof obligation is the substitution lemma itself, i.e. the substitution of the typing, which finally establishes the all-quantification.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The later cannot formally be proven, since no such syntax is at hand.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] To make programming practical recursive functions are needed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] A central property of the lambda calculus is that recursive definitions are not directly available, but can instead be expressed with a fixed point combinator.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] However, the fixpoint combinator cannot be formulated in a typed version of the lambda calculus without having a disastrous effect on the system as outlined below.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The original paper shows recursion can be realized by a combinator f i x : ∀ α .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] ( α → α ) → α {\displaystyle {\mathit {fix}}:\forall \alpha .(\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow \alpha } ({\displaystyle {\mathit {fix}}:\forall \alpha .(\alpha \rightarrow \alpha )\rightarrow \alpha }).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While the above is straightforward it does come at a price.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Type theory connects lambda calculus with computation and logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Overloading means that different functions can be defined and used with the same name.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Most programming languages at least provide overloading with the built-in arithmetic operations (+, <, etc.), to allow the programmer to write arithmetic expressions in the same form, even for different numerical types like `int` or `real`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Because a mixture of these different types within the same expression also demands for implicit conversion, overloading especially for these operations is often built into the programming language itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] In some languages, this feature is generalized and made available to the user, e.g. in C++.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While ad hoc overloading has been avoided in functional programming for the computation costs both in type checking and inference, a means to systematise overloading has been introduced that resembles both in form and naming to object oriented programming, but works one level upwards.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] "Instances" in this systematic are not objects (i.e. on value level), but rather types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Herein, the type `a` is not only polymorphic, but also restricted to be an instance of some type class `Ord`, that provides the order predicates `<` and `>=` used in the functions body.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] The proper implementations of these predicates are then passed to quicksorts as additional parameters, as soon as quicksort is used on more concrete types providing a single implementation of the overloaded function quickSort.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Because the "classes" only allow a single type as their argument, the resulting type system can still provide inference.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Additionally, the type classes can then be equipped with some kind of overloading order allowing one to arrange the classes as a lattice.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Parametric polymorphism implies that types themselves are passed as parameters as if they were proper values.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Passed as arguments to a proper functions, but also into "type functions" as in the "parametric" type constants, leads to the question how to more properly type types themselves.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Higher-order types are used to create an even more expressive type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Unification is no longer decidable in the presence of meta types, rendering type inference impossible in this extend of generality.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Additionally, assuming a type of all types that includes itself as type leads into a paradox, as in the set of all sets, so one must proceed in steps of levels of abstraction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Research in second order lambda calculus, one step upwards, showed that type inference is undecidable in this generality.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Haskell introduces one higher level named kind.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Language extensions are available which extend kinds to emulate features of a dependent type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Attempts to combine subtyping and type inference have caused quite some frustration.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] It is straightforward to accumulate and propagate subtyping constraints (as opposed to type equality constraints), making the resulting constraints part of the inferred typing schemes, for example ∀ α .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] However, because type variables are no longer unified eagerly in this approach, it tends to generate large and unwieldy typing schemes containing many useless type variables and constraints, making them hard to read and understand.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Therefore, considerable effort was put into simplifying such typing schemes and their constraints, using techniques similar to those of nondeterministic finite automaton (NFA) simplification (useful in the presence of inferred recursive types).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] More recently, Dolan and Mycroft formalized the relationship between typing scheme simplification and NFA simplification and showed that an algebraic take on the formalization of subtyping allowed generating compact principal typing schemes for an ML-like language (called MLsub).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Notably, their proposed typing scheme used a restricted form of union and intersection types instead of explicit constraints.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Parreaux later claimed that this algebraic formulation was equivalent to a relatively simple algorithm resembling Algorithm W, and that the use of union and intersection types was not essential.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] On the other hand, type inference has proven more difficult in the context of object-oriented programming languages, because object methods tend to require first-class polymorphism in the style of System F (where type inference is undecidable) and because of features like F-bounded polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Consequently, type systems with subtyping enabling object-oriented programming, such as Cardelli's system F <: {\displaystyle F_{<:}} ({\displaystyle F_{<:}}), do not support HM-style type inference.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] Row polymorphism can be used as an alternative to subtyping for supporting language features like structural records.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system-p02] While this style of polymorphism is less flexible than subtyping in some ways, notably requiring more polymorphism than strictly necessary to cope with the lack of directionality in type constraints, it has the advantage that it can be integrated with the standard HM algorithms quite easily.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] In the simply typed lambda calculus, types T are either atomic type constants or function types of form $T\rightarrow T$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Monotypes $\tau$ are syntactically represented as terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Examples of monotypes include type constants like ${\mathtt {int}}$ or ${\mathtt {string}}$ , and parametric types like ${\mathtt {Map\ (Set\ string)\ int}}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] The latter types are examples of *applications* of type functions, for example, from the set $\{{\mathtt {Map^{2},\ Set^{1},\ string^{0},\ int^{0}}},\ \rightarrow ^{2}\}$ , where the superscript indicates the number of type parameters.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] The complete set of type functions C is arbitrary in HM, except that it *must* contain at least $\rightarrow ^{2}$ , the type of functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] For example, a function mapping integers to strings has type ${\mathtt {int}}\rightarrow {\mathtt {string}}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] A function with polytype $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ can map *any* value of the same type to itself, and the identity function is a value for this type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] As another example, $\forall \alpha .({\mathtt {Set}}\ \alpha )\rightarrow {\mathtt {int}}$ is the type of a function mapping all finite sets to integers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] For instance, a type $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \forall \alpha .\alpha$ is excluded by the syntax of types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Also monotypes are included in the polytypes, thus a type has the general form $\forall \alpha _{1}\dots \forall \alpha _{n}.\tau$ , where $n\geq 0$ and $\tau$ is a monotype.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Equality of polytypes is up to reordering the quantification and renaming the quantified variables ( $\alpha$ -conversion).
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] In a type $\forall \alpha _{1}\dots \forall \alpha _{n}.\tau$ , the symbol $\forall$ is the quantifier binding the type variables $\alpha _{i}$ in the monotype $\tau$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] The variables $\alpha _{i}$ are called *quantified* and any occurrence of a quantified type variable in $\tau$ is called *bound* and all unbound type variables in $\tau$ are called *free*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Additionally to the quantification $\forall$ in polytypes, type variables can also be bound by occurring in the context, but with the inverse effect on the right hand side of the $\vdash$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Likewise in Haskell, where all type variables implicitly occur quantified, i.e. a Haskell type `a -> a` means $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ here.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Related and also very uncommon is the binding effect of the right hand side $\sigma$ of the assignments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] The constant function **K** = $\lambda x.\lambda y.x$ provides an example.
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] It has the monotype $\alpha \rightarrow \beta \rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] One can force polymorphism by $\mathbf {let} \ k=\lambda x.(\mathbf {let} \ f=\lambda y.x\ \mathbf {in} \ f)\ \mathbf {in} \ k$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] Herein, f has the type $\forall \gamma .\gamma \rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] The free monotype variable $\alpha$ originates from the type of the variable x bound in the surrounding scope. k has the type $\forall \alpha \forall \beta .\alpha \rightarrow \beta \rightarrow \alpha$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] One could imagine the free type variable $\alpha$ in the type of f be bound by the $\forall \alpha$ in the type of k .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] As an example, the identity $\lambda x.x$ can have $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ as its type as well as ${\texttt {string}}\rightarrow {\texttt {string}}$ or ${\texttt {int}}\rightarrow {\texttt {int}}$ and many others, but not ${\texttt {int}}\rightarrow {\texttt {string}}$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/hindley-milner-type-system] The most general type for this function is $\forall \alpha .\alpha \rightarrow \alpha$ , while the others are more specific and can be derived from the general one by consistently replacing another type for the *type parameter*, i.e. the quantified variable $\alpha$ .
