[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In mathematical logic, the **lambda calculus** (also written as ***λ*-calculus**) is a formal system for expressing computation based on function abstraction and application using variable binding and substitution.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Untyped lambda calculus, the topic of this article, is a universal machine, i.e. a model of computation that can be used to simulate any Turing machine (and vice versa).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] It was introduced by the mathematician Alonzo Church in the 1930s as part of his research into the foundations of mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In 1936, Church found a formulation which was logically consistent, and documented it in 1940.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The lambda calculus consists of a language of **lambda terms**, which are defined by a formal syntax, and a set of transformation rules for manipulating those terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In BNF, the syntax is $e::=x\mid \lambda x.e\mid e\,e,$ where variables *x*,*y*,*z* range over an infinite set of names.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A lambda term is syntactically valid if it can be obtained by repeated application of these three rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For convenience, parentheses can often be omitted when writing a lambda term—see Lambda calculus definition § Notation for details.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Within lambda terms, any occurrence of a variable that is not a parameter of some enclosing λ is said to be *free*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Any free occurrence of x in a term M is *bound* in $\lambda x.M$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Any free occurrence of any other variable within M remains free in $\lambda x.M$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For example, in the term $x\,y$ , both x and y occur free.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In $(\lambda x.x\,y)$ , y is free, but x in the body (i.e. after the dot) is not free, and is said to be *bound* (to the parameter).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] While y is free in $(\lambda x.x\,y)$ , it is bound in $(\lambda y.\lambda x.x\,y)$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] There are two occurrences of x in $(\lambda y.(\lambda x.x\,y)\,x)$ – one is bound, and the other is free.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] FV(M) is the set of free variables of M, i.e. such variables that occur free in M at least once.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The notation $M[x:=N]$ denotes **capture-avoiding substitution**: substituting N for every free occurrence of x in M, while avoiding variable capture.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] There are several notions of "equivalence" and "reduction" that make it possible to reduce lambda terms to equivalent lambda terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The term *redex*, short for *reducible expression*, refers to subterms that can be reduced by one of the reduction rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For example, (λ*x*.*M*) *N* is a β-redex in expressing the substitution of *N* for *x* in *M*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The expression to which a redex reduces is called its *reduct*; the reduct of (λ*x*.*M*) *N* is *M*[*x* := *N*].
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus is Turing complete, that is, it is a universal model of computation that can be used to simulate any Turing machine.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Its namesake, the Greek letter lambda (λ), is used in lambda expressions and lambda terms to denote binding a variable in a function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus may be *untyped* or *typed*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In typed lambda calculus, functions can be applied only if they are capable of accepting the given input's "type" of data.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi are strictly *weaker* than the untyped lambda calculus, which is the primary subject of this article, in the sense that *typed lambda calculi can express less* than the untyped calculus can.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] On the other hand, more things can be proven with typed lambda calculi.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For example, in simply typed lambda calculus, it is a theorem that every evaluation strategy terminates for every simply typed lambda-term, whereas evaluation of untyped lambda-terms need not terminate (see below).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] One reason there are many different typed lambda calculi has been the desire to do more (of what the untyped calculus can do) without giving up on being able to prove strong theorems about the calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus has applications in many different areas in mathematics, philosophy, linguistics, and computer science.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus has played an important role in the development of the theory of programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Functional programming languages implement lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus is also a current research topic in category theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus was introduced by mathematician Alonzo Church in the 1930s as part of an investigation into the foundations of mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The original system was shown to be logically inconsistent in 1935 when Stephen Kleene and J.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Rosser developed the Kleene–Rosser paradox.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Subsequently, in 1936 Church isolated and published just the portion relevant to computation, what is now called the untyped lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In 1940, he also introduced a computationally weaker, but logically consistent system, known as the simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Until the 1960s when its relation to programming languages was clarified, the lambda calculus was only a formalism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Thanks to Richard Montague and other linguists' applications in the semantics of natural language, the lambda calculus has begun to enjoy a respectable place in both linguistics and computer science.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] There is some uncertainty over the reason for Church's use of the Greek letter lambda (λ) as the notation for function-abstraction in the lambda calculus, perhaps in part due to conflicting explanations by Church himself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Dana Scott has also addressed this question in various public lectures.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Scott recounts that he once posed a question about the origin of the lambda symbol to Church's former student and son-in-law John W.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] According to Scott, Church's entire response consisted of returning the postcard with the following annotation: "eeny, meeny, miny, moe".
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Computable functions are a fundamental concept within computer science and mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The lambda calculus provides simple semantics for computation which are useful for formally studying properties of computation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The lambda calculus incorporates two simplifications that make its semantics simple.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The first simplification is that the lambda calculus treats functions "anonymously"; it does not give them explicit names.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] (which is read as "a tuple of x and y is mapped to ${\textstyle x^{2}+y^{2}}$ ").
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] where the input is simply mapped to itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The second simplification is that the lambda calculus only uses functions of a single input.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] An ordinary function that requires two inputs, for instance the ${\textstyle \operatorname {square\_sum} }$ function, can be reworked into an equivalent function that accepts a single input, and as output returns *another* function, that in turn accepts a single input.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This method, known as currying, transforms a function that takes multiple arguments into a chain of functions each with a single argument.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In lambda calculus, functions are taken to be 'first class values', so functions may be used as the inputs, or be returned as outputs from other functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For example, the lambda term $\lambda x.x$ represents the identity function, $x\mapsto x$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Further, $\lambda x.y$ represents the *constant function* $x\mapsto y$ , the function that always returns y , no matter the input.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] As an example of a function operating on functions, the function composition can be defined as $\lambda f.\lambda g.\lambda x.(f(gx))$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] It can be shown that β-reduction is confluent up to α-conversion (i.e. when two normal forms are considered to be equal if it is possible to α-convert one into the other).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] By the Church–Rosser theorem, any particular sequence of reduction steps starting from a given lambda term that eventually terminates will produce the same β-normal form.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] However, the untyped lambda calculus under β-reduction as a rewriting rule is neither strongly normalising nor weakly normalising; there are terms with no normal form such as **Ω**.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Considering individual terms, both strongly normalising terms and weakly normalising terms have a unique normal form.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For strongly normalising terms, any reduction strategy is guaranteed to yield the normal form, whereas for weakly normalising terms, some reduction strategies may fail to find it.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The basic lambda calculus may be used to model arithmetic, Booleans, data structures, and recursion, as illustrated in the following sub-sections *i*, *ii*, *iii*, and *§ iv*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A Church numeral is a higher-order function—it takes a single-argument function *f*, and returns another single-argument function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The Church numeral *n* is a function that takes a function *f* as argument and returns the *n*-th composition of *f*, i.e. the function *f* composed with itself *n* times.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This is denoted *f*(*n*) and is in fact the *n*-th power of *f* (considered as an operator); *f*(0) is defined to be the identity function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Functional composition is associative, and so, such repeated compositions of a single function *f* obey two laws of exponents, *f*(*m*)∘*f*(*n*) = *f*(*m+n*) and (*f*(*n*))(*m*) = *f*(*m*n*), which is why these numerals can be used for arithmetic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] One way of thinking about the Church numeral *n*, which is often useful when analyzing programs, is as an instruction 'repeat *n* times'.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For example, using the PAIR and NIL functions defined below, one can define a function that constructs a (linked) list of *n* elements all equal to *x* by repeating 'prepend another *x* element' *n* times, starting from an empty list.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] By varying what is being repeated, and what argument(s) that function being repeated is applied to, a great many different effects can be achieved.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Thus multiplication of Church numerals is simply their composition as functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] since multiplying *m* and *n* is the same as adding *n* repeatedly, *m* times, starting from zero.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Exponentiation, being the repeated multiplication of a number with itself, translates as a repeated composition of a Church numeral with itself, as a function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] but that is just an eta-expanded version of POW we already have, above.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The *predecessor* function, specified by two equations PRED (SUCC *n*) = *n* and PRED 0 = 0, is considerably more involved.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Two other definitions of PRED are given below, one using conditionals and the other using pairs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] With the predecessor function, subtraction is straightforward.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] SUB *m* *n* yields *m* − *n* when *m* > *n* and 0 otherwise.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] and we see that AND TRUE FALSE is equivalent to FALSE.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A *predicate* is a function that returns a Boolean value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] and since *m* = *n* if LEQ *m* *n* and LEQ *n* *m*, it is straightforward to build a predicate for numerical equality.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The availability of predicates and the above definition of TRUE and FALSE make it convenient to write "if-then-else" expressions in lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] which can be verified by showing inductively that *n* (λ*g*.λ*k*.ISZERO (*g* 1) *k* (PLUS (*g* *k*) 1)) (λ*v*.0) is the add *n* − 1 function for *n* > 0.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A pair (2-tuple) encapsulates two values, and is represented by an abstraction that expects a handler to which it will pass the two values.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] FIRST returns the first element of the pair, and SECOND returns the second.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A linked list can either be NIL, representing the empty list, or a PAIR of an element (so-called *head*) and a smaller list (*tail*).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] (where I := λ*x*.*x* ), evidently leading back to the original.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] There is a considerable body of programming idioms for lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Many of these were originally developed in the context of using lambda calculus as a foundation for programming language semantics, effectively using lambda calculus as a low-level programming language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Because several programming languages include the lambda calculus (or something very similar) as a fragment, these techniques also see use in practical programming, but may then be perceived as obscure or foreign.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In lambda calculus, a library would take the form of a collection of previously defined functions, which as lambda-terms are merely particular constants.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] By chaining such definitions, one can write a lambda calculus "program" as zero or more function definitions, followed by one lambda-term using those functions that constitutes the main body of the program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A notable restriction of this let is that the name *f* may not be referenced in *N*, for *N* is outside the scope of the abstraction binding *f*, which is *M*; this means a recursive function definition cannot be written with let.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The letrec construction would allow writing recursive function definitions, where the scope of the abstraction binding *f* includes *N* as well as *M*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Or self-application a-la that which leads to **Y** combinator could be used.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Recursion is when a function invokes itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] What would a value be which were to represent such a function?
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] It has to refer to itself somehow inside itself, just as the definition refers to itself inside itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] If this value were to contain itself by value, it would have to be of infinite size, which is impossible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Other notations, which support recursion natively, overcome this by referring to the function *by name* inside its definition.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Lambda calculus cannot express this, since in it there simply are no names for terms to begin with, only arguments' names, i.e. parameters in abstractions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Thus, a lambda expression can receive itself as its argument and refer to (a copy of) itself via the corresponding parameter's name.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This will work fine in case it was indeed called with itself as an argument.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] For example, (λ*x*.*x* *x*) *E* = (*E E*) will express recursion when *E* is an abstraction which is applying its parameter to itself inside its body to express a recursive call.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Since this parameter receives *E* as its value, its self-application will be the same (*E E*) again.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In the lambda expression which is to represent this function, a *parameter* (typically the first one) will be assumed to receive the lambda expression itself as its value, so that calling it with itself as its first argument will amount to the recursive call.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Here *s s* becomes *the same* (E E) inside the result of the application (E E), and using the same function for a call is the definition of what recursion is.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The application is an additional step just as the name lookup would be.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Instead of having F inside itself as a whole *up-front*, delaying its re-creation until the next call makes its existence possible by having two *finite* lambda-terms E inside it re-create it on the fly *later* as needed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This self-applicational approach solves it, but requires re-writing each recursive call as a self-application.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Given a lambda term with first argument representing recursive call (e.g.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] G here), the *fixed-point* combinator FIX will return a self-replicating lambda expression representing the recursive function (here, F).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The function does not need to be explicitly passed to itself at any point, for the self-replication is arranged in advance, when it is created, to be done each time it is called.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Thus the original lambda expression (FIX G) is re-created inside itself, at call-point, achieving self-reference.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Now, to perform the recursive call to the factorial function for an argument *n*, we would simply call (**Y** G) *n*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Every recursively defined function can be seen as a fixed point of some suitably defined higher order function (also known as functional) closing over the recursive call with an extra argument.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Therefore, using **Y**, every recursive function can be expressed as a lambda expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In particular, we can now cleanly define the subtraction, multiplication, and comparison predicates of natural numbers, using recursion.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] When Y combinator is coded directly in a strict programming language, the applicative order of evaluation used in such languages will cause an attempt to fully expand the internal self-application $(xx)$ prematurely, causing stack overflow or, in case of tail call optimization, indefinite looping.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A delayed variant of Y, the Z combinator, can be used in such languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] If *N* is a lambda-term without abstraction, but possibly containing named constants (combinators), then there exists a lambda-term *T*(*x*,*N*) which is equivalent to λ*x*.*N* but lacks abstraction (except as part of the named constants, if these are considered non-atomic).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This can also be viewed as anonymising variables, as *T*(*x*,*N*) removes all occurrences of *x* from *N*, while still allowing argument values to be substituted into the positions where *N* contains an *x*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In either case, a term of the form *T*(*x*,*N*) *P* is reduced by having the initial combinator **I**, **K**, or **S** grab the argument *P*, just like β-reduction of (λ*x*.*N*) *P* would do.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] **K** *N* throws the argument away, just like (λ*x*.*N*) does when *x* has no free occurrence in *N*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] **S** passes the argument on to both subterms of the application, and then applies the result of the first to the result of the second, just like (λ*x*.*MN*)*P* is the same as ((λ*x*.*M*)*P*) ((λ*x*.*N*)*P*).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The combinators **B** and **C** are similar to **S**, but pass the argument on to only one subterm of an application (**B** to the "argument" subterm and **C** to the "function" subterm), thus saving a subsequent **K** if there is no occurrence of *x* in one of the subterms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In comparison to **B** and **C**, the **S** combinator actually conflates two functionalities: rearranging arguments, and duplicating an argument so that it may be used in two places.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The **W** combinator does only the latter, yielding the B, C, K, W system as an alternative to SKI combinator calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A *typed lambda calculus* is a typed formalism that uses the lambda-symbol ( $\lambda$ ) to denote anonymous function abstraction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In this context, types are usually objects of a syntactic nature that are assigned to lambda terms; the exact nature of a type depends on the calculus considered (see Kinds of typed lambda calculi).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] From a certain point of view, typed lambda calculi can be seen as refinements of the untyped lambda calculus but from another point of view, they can also be considered the more fundamental theory and *untyped lambda calculus* a special case with only one type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi are foundational programming languages and are the base of typed functional programming languages such as ML and Haskell and, more indirectly, typed imperative programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi play an important role in the design of type systems for programming languages; here typability usually captures desirable properties of the program, e.g., the program will not cause a memory access violation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Typed lambda calculi are closely related to mathematical logic and proof theory via the Curry–Howard isomorphism and they can be considered as the internal language of classes of categories, e.g., the simply typed lambda calculus is the language of a Cartesian closed category (CCC).
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Whether a term is normalising or not, and how much work needs to be done in normalising it if it is, depends to a large extent on the reduction strategy used.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The leftmost outermost redex is reduced first.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] That is, whenever possible, arguments are substituted into the body of an abstraction before the arguments are reduced.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] If a term has a beta-normal form, normal order reduction will always reach that normal form.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The leftmost innermost redex is reduced first.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] As a consequence, a function's arguments are always reduced before they are substituted into the function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Unlike normal order reduction, applicative order reduction may fail to find the beta-normal form of an expression, even if such a normal form exists.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This means essentially the lack of any particular reduction strategy—with regard to reducibility, "all bets are off".
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Like applicative order, but no reductions are performed inside abstractions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This is similar to the evaluation order of strict languages like C: the arguments to a function are evaluated before calling the function, and function bodies are not even partially evaluated until the arguments are substituted in.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Like normal order, but no reductions are performed inside abstractions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] As normal order, but computations that have the same label are reduced simultaneously.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] As call by name (hence weak), but function applications that would duplicate terms instead name the argument.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The argument may be evaluated "when needed", at which point the name binding is updated with the reduced value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This can save time compared to normal order evaluation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] There is no algorithm that takes as input any two lambda expressions and outputs TRUE or FALSE depending on whether one expression reduces to the other.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] More precisely, no computable function can decide the question.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This was historically the first problem for which undecidability could be proven.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] As usual for such a proof, *computable* means computable by any model of computation that is Turing complete.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] See the Church–Turing thesis for other approaches to defining computability and their equivalence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Church's proof of uncomputability first reduces the problem to determining whether a given lambda expression has a normal form.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Then he assumes that this predicate is computable, and can hence be expressed in lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Building on earlier work by Kleene and constructing a Gödel numbering for lambda expressions, he constructs a lambda expression *e* that closely follows the proof of Gödel's first incompleteness theorem.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] If *e* is applied to its own Gödel number, a contradiction results.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The notion of computational complexity for the lambda calculus is a bit tricky, because the cost of a β-reduction may vary depending on how it is implemented.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] To be precise, one must somehow find the location of all of the occurrences of the bound variable *V* in the expression *E*, implying a time cost, or one must keep track of the locations of free variables in some way, implying a space cost.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] A naïve search for the locations of *V* in *E* is *O*(*n*) in the length *n* of *E*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Director strings were an early approach that traded this time cost for a quadratic space usage.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] More generally this has led to the study of systems that use explicit substitution.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In 2014, it was shown that the number of β-reduction steps taken by normal order reduction to reduce a term is a *reasonable* time cost model, that is, the reduction can be simulated on a Turing machine in time polynomially proportional to the number of steps.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This was a long-standing open problem, due to *size explosion*, the existence of lambda terms which grow exponentially in size for each β-reduction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The result gets around this by working with a compact shared representation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The result makes clear that the amount of space needed to evaluate a lambda term is not proportional to the size of the term during reduction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] It is not currently known what a good measure of space complexity would be.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] An unreasonable model does not necessarily mean inefficient.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Optimal reduction reduces all computations with the same label in one step, avoiding duplicated work, but the number of parallel β-reduction steps to reduce a given term to normal form is approximately linear in the size of the term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This is far too small to be a reasonable cost measure, as any Turing machine may be encoded in the lambda calculus in size linearly proportional to the size of the Turing machine.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The true cost of reducing lambda terms is not due to β-reduction per se but rather the handling of the duplication of redexes during β-reduction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In addition the BOHM prototype implementation of optimal reduction outperformed both Caml Light and Haskell on pure lambda terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The above example is an expression that evaluates to a first-class function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The symbol `lambda` creates an anonymous function, given a list of parameter names—just the single argument `x`, in this case—and an expression that is evaluated as the body of the function, `x**2`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Pascal and many other imperative languages have long supported passing subprograms as arguments to other subprograms through the mechanism of function pointers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] However, function pointers are an insufficient condition for functions to be first class datatypes, because a function is a first class datatype if and only if new instances of the function can be created at runtime.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Such runtime creation of functions is supported in Smalltalk, JavaScript, Wolfram Language, and more recently in Scala, Eiffel (as agents), C# (as delegates) and C++11, among others.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The Church–Rosser property of the lambda calculus means that evaluation (β-reduction) can be carried out in *any order*, even in parallel.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This means that various nondeterministic evaluation strategies are relevant.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] However, the lambda calculus does not offer any explicit constructs for parallelism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] One can add constructs such as futures to the lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Other process calculi have been developed for describing communication and concurrency.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The fact that lambda calculus terms act as functions on other lambda calculus terms, and even on themselves, led to questions about the semantics of the lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] Could a sensible meaning be assigned to lambda calculus terms?
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] The natural semantics was to find a set *D* isomorphic to the function space *D* → *D*, of functions on itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] However, no nontrivial such *D* can exist, by cardinality constraints because the set of all functions from *D* to *D* has greater cardinality than *D*, unless *D* is a singleton set.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] In the 1970s, Dana Scott showed that if only continuous functions were considered, a set or domain *D* with the required property could be found, thus providing a model for the lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/lambda-calculus] This work also formed the basis for the denotational semantics of programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] In programming language theory and type theory, **polymorphism** allows a value or variable to have more than one type and allows a given operation to be performed on values of more than one type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] In object-oriented programming, polymorphism is the provision of one interface to entities of different data types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] The concept is borrowed from a principle in biology in which an organism or species can have many different forms or stages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Interest in polymorphic type systems developed significantly in the 1990s, with practical implementations beginning to appear by the end of the decade.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] *Ad hoc polymorphism* and *parametric polymorphism* were originally described in Christopher Strachey's *Fundamental Concepts in Programming Languages*, where they are listed as "the two main classes" of polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Ad hoc polymorphism was a feature of ALGOL 68, while parametric polymorphism was the core feature of ML's type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] In a 1985 paper, Peter Wegner and Luca Cardelli introduced the term *inclusion polymorphism* to model subtypes and inheritance, citing Simula as the first programming language to implement it.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Christopher Strachey chose the term *ad hoc polymorphism* to refer to polymorphic functions that can be applied to arguments of different types, but that behave differently depending on the type of the argument to which they are applied (also known as function overloading or operator overloading).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] "Ad hoc" here means that this form of polymorphism is not a fundamental feature of the type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] In dynamically typed languages the situation can be more complex, as the correct function that needs to be invoked might only be determinable at run time.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Implicit type conversion has also been defined as a form of polymorphism, referred to as "coercion polymorphism".
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] The concept of parametric polymorphism applies to both data types and functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Parametric polymorphism is ubiquitous in functional programming, where it is often simply referred to as "polymorphism".
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Parametric polymorphism is also available in several object-oriented languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Reynolds (and later Jean-Yves Girard) formally developed this notion of polymorphism as an extension to lambda calculus (called the polymorphic lambda calculus or System F).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Any parametrically polymorphic function is necessarily restricted in what it can do, working on the shape of the data instead of its value, leading to the concept of parametricity.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Some languages employ the idea of *subtyping* (also called *subtype polymorphism* or *inclusion polymorphism*) to restrict the range of types that can be used in a particular case of polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] In these languages, subtyping allows a function to be written to take an object of a certain type *T*, but also work correctly if passed an object that belongs to a type *S* that is a subtype of *T* (according to the Liskov substitution principle).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] This type relation is sometimes written *S* <: *T*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Conversely, *T* is said to be a *supertype* of *S*, written *T* :> *S*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Subtype polymorphism is usually resolved dynamically (see below).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] In the following Java example cats and dogs are made subtypes of pets.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] The actual type of the object can be hidden from clients into a black box, and accessed via object identity.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] If the *Number* type is *abstract*, it may not be possible to access an object whose *most-derived* type is *Number* (see abstract data type, abstract class).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] This particular kind of type hierarchy is known, especially in the context of the Scheme language, as a *numerical tower*, and usually contains many more types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Object-oriented programming languages offer subtype polymorphism using *subclassing* (also known as *inheritance*).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] The same goes for most other popular object systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Some, however, such as Common Lisp Object System, provide *multiple dispatch*, under which method calls are polymorphic in all arguments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] The interaction between parametric polymorphism and subtyping leads to the concepts of type variance and bounded quantification.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Row polymorphism is a similar, but distinct concept from subtyping.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] It allows the usage of all values whose types have certain properties, without losing the remaining type information.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] A related concept is *polytypism* (or *data type genericity*).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] A polytypic function is more general than polymorphic, and in such a function, "though one can provide fixed ad hoc cases for specific data types, an ad hoc combinator is absent".
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Rank polymorphism is one of the defining features of the array programming languages, like APL.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] The essence of the rank-polymorphic programming model is implicitly treating all operations as aggregate operations, usable on arrays with arbitrarily many dimensions, which is to say that rank polymorphism allows functions to be defined to operate on arrays of any shape and size.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Polymorphism can be distinguished by when the implementation is selected: statically (at compile time) or dynamically (at run time, typically via a virtual function).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] This is known respectively as *static dispatch* and *dynamic dispatch,* and the corresponding forms of polymorphism are accordingly called *static polymorphism* and *dynamic polymorphism*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Static polymorphism executes faster, because there is no dynamic dispatch overhead, but requires additional compiler support.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Further, static polymorphism allows greater static analysis by compilers (notably for optimization), source code analysis tools, and human readers (programmers).
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Dynamic polymorphism is more flexible but slower—for example, dynamic polymorphism allows duck typing, and a dynamically linked library may operate on objects without knowing their full type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] Static polymorphism typically occurs in ad hoc polymorphism and parametric polymorphism, whereas dynamic polymorphism is usual for subtype polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] However, it is possible to achieve static polymorphism with subtyping through more sophisticated use of template metaprogramming, namely the curiously recurring template pattern.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] When polymorphism is exposed via a library, static polymorphism becomes impossible for dynamic libraries as there is no way of knowing what types the parameters are when the shared object is built.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] While languages like C++ and Rust use monomorphized templates, the Swift programming language makes extensive use of dynamic dispatch to build the application binary interface for these libraries by default.
[src:lambda-type-theory/polymorphism-computer-science] As a result, more code can be shared for a reduced system size at the cost of runtime overhead.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In type theory, **type inference** (sometimes called **type reconstruction**) is the automatic detection of the type of an expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] These include programming languages and mathematical type systems, but also natural languages in some branches of computer science and linguistics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In a typed language, a term's type determines the ways it can and cannot be used in that language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] At best it might be metaphor; bending type rules is a feature of poetic language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] A term's type can also affect the interpretation of operations involving that term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] For instance, "a song" is of composable type, so we interpret it as the thing created in the phrase "write a song".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] On the other hand, "a friend" is of recipient type, so we interpret it as the addressee in the phrase "write a friend".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In normal language, we would be surprised if "write a song" meant addressing a letter to a song or "write a friend" meant drafting a friend on paper.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Terms with different types can even refer to materially the same thing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] For example, we would interpret "to hang up the clothes line" as putting it into use, but "to hang up the leash" as putting it away, even though, in context, both "clothes line" and "leash" might refer the same rope, just at different times.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Typings are often used to prevent an object from being considered too generally.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] For instance, if the type system treats all numbers as the same, then a programmer who accidentally writes code where `4` is supposed to mean "4 seconds" but is interpreted as "4 meters" would have no warning of their mistake until it caused problems at runtime.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] By incorporating units into the type system, these mistakes can be detected much earlier.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] As another example, Russell's paradox arises when anything can be a set element and any predicate can define a set, but more careful typing gives several ways to resolve the paradox.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In fact, Russell's paradox sparked early versions of type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Especially in programming languages, there may not be much shared background knowledge available to the computer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In manifestly typed languages, this means that most types have to be declared explicitly.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Type inference aims to alleviate this burden, freeing the author from declaring types that the computer should be able to deduce from context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In a typing, an expression E is opposed to a type T, formally written as E : T.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Usually a typing only makes sense within some context, which is omitted here.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] If there is a way to derive a type for E, then we have accomplished *type inference*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Given only a type, is there any expression for it or does the type have no values?
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] For the simply typed lambda calculus, all three questions are decidable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The situation is not as comfortable when more expressive types are allowed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Types are a feature present in some strongly statically typed languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] It is often characteristic of functional programming languages in general.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The majority of them use a simple form of type inference; the Hindley–Milner type system can provide more complete type inference.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The ability to infer types automatically makes many programming tasks easier, leaving the programmer free to omit type annotations while still permitting type checking.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In some programming languages, all values have a data type explicitly declared at compile time, limiting the values a particular expression can take on at run-time.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Increasingly, just-in-time compilation blurs the distinction between run time and compile time.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] However, historically, if the type of a value is known only at run-time, these languages are dynamically typed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In other languages, the type of an expression is known only at compile time; these languages are statically typed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In most statically typed languages, the input and output types of functions and local variables ordinarily must be explicitly provided by type annotations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The signature of this function definition, `int increment(int x)`, declares that `increment()` is a function that takes one argument, an integer, and returns an integer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] `int result;` declares that the local variable `result` is an integer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] This is identical to how code is written in the language Dart, except that it is subject to some added constraints as described below.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] It would be possible to *infer* the types of all the variables at compile time.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In the example above, the compiler would infer that `result` and `x` have type integer since the constant `1` is type integer, and hence that `increment()` is a function `int -> int`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The variable `result2` isn't used in a legal manner, so it wouldn't have a type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In the imaginary language in which the last example is written, the compiler would assume that, in the absence of information to the contrary, `+` takes two integers and returns one integer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] (This is how it works in, for example, OCaml.) From this, the type inferencer can infer that the type of `x + 1` is an integer, which means `result` is an integer and thus the return value of `add_one` is an integer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Similarly, since `+` requires both of its arguments be of the same type, `x` must be an integer, and thus, `add_one` accepts one integer as an argument.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] However, in the subsequent line, `result2` is calculated by adding a decimal `1.0` with floating-point arithmetic, causing a conflict in the use of `x` for both integer and floating-point expressions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The correct type-inference algorithm for such a situation has been known since 1958 and has been known to be correct since 1982.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] It revisits the prior inferences and uses the most general type from the outset: in this case floating-point.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] This can however have detrimental implications, for instance using a floating-point from the outset can introduce precision issues that would have not been there with an integer type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Frequently, however, degenerate type-inference algorithms are used that cannot backtrack and instead generate an error message in such a situation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] This behavior may be preferable as type inference may not always be neutral algorithmically, as illustrated by the prior floating-point precision issue.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] An algorithm of intermediate generality implicitly declares `result2` as a floating-point variable, and the addition implicitly converts `x` to a floating point.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] This can be correct if the calling contexts never supply a floating point argument.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Such a situation shows the difference between *type inference*, which does not involve type conversion, and implicit type conversion, which forces data to a different data type, often without restrictions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Finally, a significant downside of complex type-inference algorithm is that the resulting type inference resolution is not going to be obvious to humans (notably because of the backtracking), which can be detrimental as code is primarily intended to be comprehensible to humans.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The recent emergence of just-in-time compilation allows for hybrid approaches where the type of arguments supplied by the various calling context is known at compile time, and can generate a large number of compiled versions of the same function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Each compiled version can then be optimized for a different set of types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] A version that accepts an integer input and uses implicit type conversion.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] A version that accepts a floating-point number as input and uses floating point instructions throughout.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Type inference is the ability to automatically deduce, either partially or fully, the type of an expression at compile time.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The compiler is often able to infer the type of a variable or the type signature of a function, without explicit type annotations having been given.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In many cases, it is possible to omit type annotations from a program completely if the type inference system is robust enough, or the program or language is simple enough.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] It is through recognition of the eventual reduction of expressions to implicitly typed atomic values that the compiler for a type inferring language is able to compile a program completely without type annotations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In complex forms of higher-order programming and polymorphism, it is not always possible for the compiler to infer as much, and type annotations are occasionally necessary for disambiguation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] For instance, type inference with polymorphic recursion is known to be undecidable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Furthermore, explicit type annotations can be used to optimize code by forcing the compiler to use a more specific (faster/smaller) type than it had inferred.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Some methods for type inference are based on constraint satisfaction or satisfiability modulo theories.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] (Recall that `:` in Haskell denotes cons, structuring a head element and a list tail into a bigger list or destructuring a nonempty list into its head element and its tail.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Type inference on the `map` function proceeds as follows.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] `map` is a function of two arguments, so its type is constrained to be of the form `a -> b -> c`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In Haskell, the patterns `[]` and `(first:rest)` always match lists, so the second argument must be a list type: `b = [d]` for some type `d`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Its first argument `f` is applied to the argument `first`, which must have type `d`, corresponding with the type in the list argument, so `f :: d -> e` (`::` means "is of type") for some type `e`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The return value of `map f`, finally, is a list of whatever `f` produces, so `[e]`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Putting the parts together leads to `map :: (d -> e) -> [d] -> [e]`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] It turns out that this is also the most general type, since no further constraints apply.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] As the inferred type of `map` is parametrically polymorphic, the type of the arguments and results of `f` are not inferred, but left as type variables, and so `map` can be applied to functions and lists of various types, as long as the actual types match in each invocation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The algorithms used by programs like compilers are equivalent to the informally structured reasoning above, but a bit more verbose and methodical.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The exact details depend on the inference algorithm chosen (see the following section for the best-known algorithm), but the example below gives the general idea.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] We also constrain the left and right sides of each equation to unify with each other: `κ ~ [δ]` and `μ ~ ο`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Then we substitute until no further variables can be eliminated.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The exact order is immaterial; if the code type-checks, any order will lead to the same final form.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] No more substitutions are possible, and relabeling gives us `map :: (a -> b) -> [a] -> [b]`, the same as we found without going into these details.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The algorithm first used to perform type inference is now informally termed the Hindley–Milner algorithm, although the algorithm should properly be attributed to Damas and Milner.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] It is also traditionally called *type reconstruction*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] If a term is well-typed in accordance with Hindley–Milner typing rules, then the rules generate a principal typing for the term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The process of discovering this principal typing is the process of "reconstruction".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] The origin of this algorithm is the type inference algorithm for the simply typed lambda calculus that was devised by Haskell Curry and Robert Feys in 1958.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In 1978 Robin Milner, independently of Hindley's work, provided an equivalent algorithm, Algorithm W.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] In 1982 Luis Damas finally proved that Milner's algorithm is complete and extended it to support systems with polymorphic references.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] By design, type inference will infer the most general type appropriate.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] However, many languages, especially older programming languages, have slightly unsound type systems, where using a more general types may not always be algorithmically neutral.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Type inference algorithms have been used to analyze natural languages as well as programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-inference] Type inference algorithms are also used in some grammar induction and constraint-based grammar systems for natural languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A programming language consists of a system of allowed sequences of symbols (constructs) together with rules that define how each construct is interpreted.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, a language might allow expressions representing various types of data, expressions that provide structuring rules for data, expressions representing various operations on data, and constructs that provide sequencing rules for the order in which to perform operations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A simple type system for a programming language is a set of rules that associates a *data type* (for example, integer, floating point, string) with each *term* (data-valued expression) in a computer program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In more ambitious type systems, a variety of constructs, such as variables, expressions, functions, and modules, may be assigned types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type systems formalize and enforce the otherwise implicit categories the programmer uses for algebraic data types, data structures, or other data types, such as "string", "array of float", "function returning boolean".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The main purpose of a type system in a programming language is to reduce possibilities for bugs in computer programs due to mismatches in how values are interpreted in different parts of a program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The aim is to prevent operations expecting a certain kind of value from being applied to values for which that operation does not make sense (validity errors).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A type system can detect and prevent some of these mismatches.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] When a type mismatch is detected, it is called a type error.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The type of a term constrains the contexts in which it may be used.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For a variable, the type system determines the allowed values of that variable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For that variable to be presented as a parameter to an operation, the operation must be able to accept in that parameter any value that the type of the variable allows.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type systems are typically specified as part of programming language design.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] They are built into interpreters and compilers for the language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In some languages, the type system can be extended by optional tools that perform added checks using the language's original type syntax and grammar.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type systems allow defining interfaces between different parts of a computer program, and then checking that the parts have been connected in a consistent way.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This checking can happen statically (at compile time), dynamically (at runtime), or as a combination of both.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type systems have other purposes as well, such as expressing business rules, enabling certain compiler optimizations, allowing for multiple dispatch, and providing a form of documentation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] An example of a simple type system is that of the C language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The portions of a C program are the function definitions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] One function is invoked by another function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The interface of a function states the name of the function and a list of parameters that are passed to the function's code.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The code of an invoking function states the name of the invoked, along with the names of variables that hold values to pass to it.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] During a computer program's execution, the values are placed into temporary storage, then execution jumps to the code of the invoked function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The invoked function's code accesses the values and makes use of them.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If the instructions inside the function are written with the assumption of receiving an integer value, but the calling code passed a floating-point value, then the wrong result will be computed by the invoked function.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The C compiler checks the types of the arguments passed to a function when it is called against the types of the parameters declared in the function's definition.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If the types do not match, the compiler throws a compile-time error or warning.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A compiler may also use the static type of a value to optimize the storage it needs and the choice of algorithms for operations on the value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In many C compilers the *float* data type, for example, is represented in 32 bits, in accord with the IEEE specification for single-precision floating point numbers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] They will thus use floating-point-specific microprocessor operations on those values (floating-point addition, multiplication, etc.).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The depth of type constraints and the manner of their evaluation affect the *typing* of the language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A programming language may further associate an operation with various resolutions for each type, in the case of type polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type theory is the study of type systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The concrete types of some programming languages, such as integers and strings, depend on practical issues of computer architecture, compiler implementation, and language design.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Formally, type theory studies type systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A programming language must have the opportunity to type check using the *type system* whether at compile time or runtime, manually annotated or automatically inferred.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Assigning a data type, termed *typing*, gives meaning to a sequence of bits such as a value in memory or some object such as a variable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Associating a sequence of bits with a type conveys that meaning to the programmable hardware to form a *symbolic system* composed of that hardware and some program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A program associates each value with at least one specific type, but it also can occur that one value is associated with many subtypes.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Other entities, such as objects, modules, communication channels, and dependencies can become associated with a type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Even a type can become associated with a type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] An implementation of a *type system* could in theory associate identifications called *data type* (a type of a value), *class* (a type of an object), and *kind* (a *type of a type*, or metatype).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] These are the abstractions that typing can go through, on a hierarchy of levels contained in a system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] It is challenging to find a sufficiently expressive type system that satisfies all programming practices in a type safe manner.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A programming language compiler can also implement a *dependent type* or an *effect system*, which enables even more program specifications to be verified by a type checker.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Beyond simple value-type pairs, a virtual "region" of code is associated with an "effect" component describing *what* is being done *with what*, and enabling for example to "throw" an error report.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Thus the symbolic system may be a *type and effect system*, which endows it with more safety checking than type checking alone.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Whether automated by the compiler or specified by a programmer, a type system renders program behavior illegal if it falls outside the type-system rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A type error occurs when an operation receives a different type of data than it expected.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, a type error would happen if a line of code divides two integers, and is passed a string of letters instead of an integer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] It is an unintended condition which might manifest in multiple stages of a program's development.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Thus a facility for detection of the error is needed in the type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In some languages, such as Haskell, for which type inference is automated, lint might be available to its compiler to aid in the detection of error.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type safety contributes to program correctness, but might only guarantee correctness at the cost of making the type checking itself an undecidable problem (as in the halting problem).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In a *type system* with automated type checking, a program may prove to run incorrectly yet produce no compiler errors.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Division by zero is an unsafe and incorrect operation, but a type checker which only runs at compile time does not scan for division by zero in most languages; that division would surface as a runtime error.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] To prove the absence of these defects, other kinds of formal methods, collectively known as program analyses, are in common use.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Alternatively, a sufficiently expressive type system, such as in dependently typed languages, can prevent these kinds of errors (for example, expressing *the type of non-zero numbers*).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In addition, software testing is an empirical method for finding errors that such a type checker would not detect.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The process of verifying and enforcing the constraints of types, *type checking*, may occur at compile time (a static check) or at runtime (a dynamic check).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If a language specification requires its typing rules strongly, more or less allowing only those automatic type conversions that do not lose information, one can refer to the process as *strongly typed*; if not, as *weakly typed*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The terms are not usually used in a strict sense.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Static type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program based on analysis of a program's text (source code).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If a program passes a static type checker, then the program is guaranteed to satisfy some set of type safety properties for all possible inputs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Static type checking can be considered a limited form of program verification (see type safety), and in a type-safe language, can also be considered an optimization.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If a compiler can prove that a program is well-typed, then it does not need to emit dynamic safety checks, allowing the resulting compiled binary to run faster and to be smaller.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Static type checking for Turing-complete languages is inherently conservative.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Even if the expression `<complex test>` always evaluates to `true` at runtime, most type checkers will reject the program as ill-typed, because it is difficult (if not impossible) for a static analyzer to determine that the `else` branch will not be taken.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Consequently, a static type checker will quickly detect type errors in rarely used code paths.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Without static type checking, even code coverage tests with 100% coverage may be unable to find such type errors.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The tests may fail to detect such type errors, because the combination of all places where values are created and all places where a certain value is used must be taken into account.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A number of useful and common programming language features cannot be checked statically, such as downcasting.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Thus, many languages will have both static and dynamic type checking; the static type checker verifies what it can, and dynamic checks verify the rest.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Many languages with static type checking provide a way to bypass the type checker.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Some languages allow programmers to choose between static and dynamic type safety.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, historically C# declares variables statically, but C# 4.0 introduces the `dynamic` keyword, which is used to declare variables to be checked dynamically at runtime.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Other languages allow writing code that is not type-safe; for example, in C, programmers can freely cast a value between any two types that have the same size, effectively subverting the type concept.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Dynamic type checking is the process of verifying the type safety of a program at runtime.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Implementations of dynamically type-checked languages generally associate each runtime object with a *type tag* (i.e., a reference to a type) containing its type information.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This runtime type information (RTTI) can also be used to implement dynamic dispatch, late binding, downcasting, reflective programming (reflection), and similar features.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Most type-safe languages include some form of dynamic type checking, even if they also have a static type checker.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The reason for this is that many useful features or properties are difficult or impossible to verify statically.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, suppose that a program defines two types, A and B, where B is a subtype of A.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If the program tries to convert a value of type A to type B, which is known as downcasting, then the operation is legal only if the value being converted is actually a value of type B.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Thus, a dynamic check is needed to verify that the operation is safe.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This requirement is one of the criticisms of downcasting.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] By definition, dynamic type checking may cause a program to fail at runtime.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In some programming languages, it is possible to anticipate and recover from these failures.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In others, type-checking errors are considered fatal.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Programming languages that include dynamic type checking but not static type checking are often called "dynamically typed programming languages".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Certain languages allow both static and dynamic typing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, Java and some other ostensibly statically typed languages support downcasting types to their subtypes, querying an object to discover its dynamic type and other type operations that depend on runtime type information.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] More generally, most programming languages include mechanisms for dispatching over different 'kinds' of data, such as disjoint unions, runtime polymorphism, and variant types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Even when not interacting with type annotations or type checking, such mechanisms are materially similar to dynamic typing implementations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Objects in object-oriented languages are usually accessed by a reference whose static target type (or manifest type) is equal to either the object's runtime type (its latent type) or a supertype thereof.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This is conformant with the Liskov substitution principle, which states that all operations performed on an instance of a given type can also be performed on an instance of a subtype.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This concept is also known as subsumption or subtype polymorphism.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In some languages subtypes may also possess covariant or contravariant return types and argument types respectively.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Certain languages, for example Clojure, Common Lisp, or Cython are dynamically type checked by default, but allow programs to opt into static type checking by providing optional annotations.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] One reason to use such hints would be to optimize the performance of critical sections of a program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The programming environment *DrRacket*, a pedagogic environment based on Lisp, and a precursor of the language Racket is also soft-typed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Conversely, as of version 4.0, the C# language provides a way to indicate that a variable should not be statically type checked.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A variable whose type is `dynamic` will not be subject to static type checking.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Instead, the program relies on runtime type information to determine how the variable may be used.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In Rust, the `dyn std::any::Any` trait object provides dynamic typing of types containing no or only `'static` lifetimes.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The choice between static and dynamic typing requires certain trade-offs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Static typing can find type errors reliably at compile time, which increases the reliability of the delivered program.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] However, programmers disagree over how commonly type errors occur, resulting in further disagreements over the proportion of those bugs that are coded that would be caught by appropriately representing the designed types in code.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Static typing advocates believe programs are more reliable when they have been well type-checked, whereas dynamic-typing advocates point to distributed code that has proven reliable and to small bug databases.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The value of static typing increases as the strength of the type system is increased.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Advocates of dependent typing, implemented in languages such as Dependent ML and Epigram, have suggested that almost all bugs can be considered type errors, if the types used in a program are properly declared by the programmer or correctly inferred by the compiler.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Static typing usually results in compiled code that executes faster.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] When the compiler knows the exact data types that are in use (which is necessary for static verification, either through declaration or inference) it can produce optimized machine code.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Some dynamically typed languages such as Common Lisp allow optional type declarations for optimization for this reason.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] By contrast, dynamic typing may allow compilers to run faster and interpreters to dynamically load new code, because changes to source code in dynamically typed languages may result in less checking to perform and less code to revisit.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This too may reduce the edit-compile-test-debug cycle.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Statically typed languages that lack type inference (such as C and Java prior to version 10) require that programmers declare the types that a method or function must use.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This can serve as added program documentation, that is active and dynamic, instead of static.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This allows a compiler to prevent it from drifting out of synchrony, and from being ignored by programmers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] However, a language can be statically typed without requiring type declarations (examples include Haskell, Scala, OCaml, F#, Swift, and to a lesser extent C# and C++), so explicit type declaration is not required for static typing in all languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Dynamic typing allows constructs that some (simple) static type checking would reject as illegal.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, *eval* functions, which execute arbitrary data as code, become possible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] An *eval* function is possible with static typing, but requires advanced uses of algebraic data types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Further, dynamic typing better accommodates transitional code and prototyping, such as allowing a placeholder data structure (mock object) to be transparently used in place of a full data structure (usually for the purposes of experimentation and testing).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Dynamic typing typically allows duck typing (which enables easier code reuse).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Many languages with static typing also feature duck typing or other mechanisms like generic programming that also enable easier code reuse.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Dynamic typing typically makes metaprogramming easier to use.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, C++ templates are typically more cumbersome to write than the equivalent Ruby or Python code since C++ has stronger rules regarding type definitions (for both functions and variables).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This forces a developer to write more boilerplate code for a template than a Python developer would need to.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] More advanced runtime constructs such as metaclasses and introspection are often harder to use in statically typed languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In some languages, such features may also be used e.g. to generate new types and behaviors on the fly, based on runtime data.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Such advanced constructs are often provided by dynamic programming languages; many of these are dynamically typed, although *dynamic typing* need not be related to *dynamic programming languages*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Languages are often colloquially referred to as *strongly typed* or *weakly typed*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In fact, there is no universally accepted definition of what these terms mean.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In general, there are more precise terms to represent the differences between type systems that lead people to call them "strong" or "weak".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A third way of categorizing the type system of a programming language is by the safety of typed operations and conversions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *type-safe language* to describe languages that do not allow operations or conversions that violate the rules of the type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Computer scientists use the term *memory-safe language* (or just *safe language*) to describe languages that do not allow programs to access memory that has not been assigned for their use.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, a memory-safe language will check array bounds, or else statically guarantee (i.e., at compile time before execution) that array accesses out of the array boundaries will cause compile-time and perhaps runtime errors.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In this example, the variable `z` will have the value 42.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Although this may not be what the programmer anticipated, it is a well-defined result.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If `y` were a different string, one that could not be converted to a number (e.g., "Hello, World"), the result would be well-defined also.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A program can be type-safe or memory-safe and still crash on an invalid operation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This is for languages where the type system is not sufficiently advanced to precisely specify the validity of operations on all possible operands.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] But if a program encounters an operation that is not type-safe, terminating the program is often the only option.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In this example `z` will point to a memory address five characters beyond `y`, equivalent to three characters after the terminating zero character of the string pointed to by `y`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This is memory that the program is not expected to access.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In C terms this is simply undefined behaviour and the program may do anything; with a simple compiler it might actually print whatever byte is stored after the string "37".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] As this example shows, C is not memory-safe.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] As arbitrary data was assumed to be a character, it is also not a type-safe language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In general, type-safety and memory-safety go hand in hand.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, a language that supports pointer arithmetic and number-to-pointer conversions (like C) is neither memory-safe nor type-safe, because it allows arbitrary memory to be accessed as if it were valid memory of any type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Some languages allow different levels of checking to apply to different regions of code.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Additional tools such as lint and IBM Rational Purify can also be used to achieve a higher level of strictness.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] It has been proposed, chiefly by Gilad Bracha, that the choice of type system be made independent of choice of language; that a type system should be a module that can be *plugged* into a language as needed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] He believes this is advantageous, because what he calls mandatory type systems make languages less expressive and code more fragile.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The requirement that the type system does not affect the semantics of the language is difficult to fulfill.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Optional typing is related to, but distinct from, gradual typing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] While both typing disciplines can be used to perform static analysis of code (static typing), optional type systems do not enforce type safety at runtime (dynamic typing).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The term *polymorphism* refers to the ability of code (especially, functions or classes) to act on values of multiple types, or to the ability of different instances of the same data structure to contain elements of different types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type systems that allow polymorphism generally do so to improve the potential for code re-use: in a language with polymorphism, programmers need only implement a data structure such as a list or an associative array once, rather than once for each type of element with which they plan to use it.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For this reason computer scientists sometimes call the use of certain forms of polymorphism *generic programming*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The type-theoretic foundations of polymorphism are closely related to those of abstraction, modularity and (in some cases) subtyping.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Many type systems have been created that are specialized for use in certain environments with certain types of data, or for out-of-band static program analysis.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Frequently, these are based on ideas from formal type theory and are only available as part of prototype research systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The following table gives an overview over type theoretic concepts that are used in specialized type systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The names M, N, O range over terms and the names $\sigma ,\tau$ range over types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Also referred to as *dependent sum type*, since ${\textstyle (x:\sigma )\times \tau =\sum _{x:\sigma }\tau }$ .
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Dependent types are based on the idea of using scalars or values to more precisely describe the type of some other value.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, $\mathrm {matrix} (3,3)$ might be the type of a $3\times 3$ matrix.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] where k, m, n are arbitrary positive integer values.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A variant of ML called Dependent ML has been created based on this type system, but because type checking for conventional dependent types is undecidable, not all programs using them can be type-checked without some kind of limits.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Dependent ML limits the sort of equality it can decide to Presburger arithmetic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Other languages such as Epigram make the value of all expressions in the language decidable so that type checking can be decidable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] However, in general proof of decidability is undecidable, so many programs require hand-written annotations that may be very non-trivial.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] As this impedes the development process, many language implementations provide an easy way out in the form of an option to disable this condition.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This, however, comes at the cost of making the type-checker run in an infinite loop when fed programs that do not type-check, causing the compilation to fail.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Linear types, based on the theory of linear logic, and closely related to uniqueness types, are types assigned to values having the property that they have one and only one reference to them at all times.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] These are valuable for describing large immutable values such as files, strings, and so on, because any operation that simultaneously destroys a linear object and creates a similar object (such as `str = str + "a"`) can be optimized "under the hood" into an in-place mutation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Normally this is not possible, as such mutations could cause side effects on parts of the program holding other references to the object, violating referential transparency.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] They are also used in the prototype operating system Singularity for interprocess communication, statically ensuring that processes cannot share objects in shared memory to prevent race conditions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The Clean language (a Haskell-like language) uses this type system to gain a lot of speed (compared to performing a deep copy) while remaining safe.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Intersection types are types describing values that belong to *both* of two other given types with overlapping value sets.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, in most implementations of C the signed char has range -128 to 127 and the unsigned char has range 0 to 255, so the intersection type of these two types would have range 0 to 127.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Such an intersection type could be safely passed into functions expecting *either* signed or unsigned chars, because it is compatible with both types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Such a function could be passed into another function expecting an "`int` → `int`" function safely; it simply would not use the "`float` → `float`" functionality.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the intersection of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the most derived type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The intersection of sibling types is empty.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The Forsythe language includes a general implementation of intersection types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Union types are types describing values that belong to *either* of two types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, in C, the signed char has a -128 to 127 range, and the unsigned char has a 0 to 255 range, so the union of these two types would have an overall "virtual" range of -128 to 255 that may be used partially depending on which union member is accessed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Any function handling this union type would have to deal with integers in this complete range.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] More generally, the only valid operations on a union type are operations that are valid on *both* types being unioned.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] C's "union" concept is similar to union types, but is not typesafe, as it permits operations that are valid on *either* type, rather than *both*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Union types are important in program analysis, where they are used to represent symbolic values whose exact nature (e.g., value or type) is not known.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In a subclassing hierarchy, the union of a type and an ancestor type (such as its parent) is the ancestor type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The union of sibling types is a subtype of their common ancestor (that is, all operations permitted on their common ancestor are permitted on the union type, but they may also have other valid operations in common).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Existential types are frequently used in connection with record types to represent modules and abstract data types, due to their ability to separate implementation from interface.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, the type "T = ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }" describes a module interface that has a data member named *a* of type *X* and a function named *f* that takes a parameter of the *same* type *X* and returns an integer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] These types are both subtypes of the more general existential type T and correspond to concrete implementation types, so any value of one of these types is a value of type T.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Given a value "t" of type "T", we know that "t.f(t.a)" is well-typed, regardless of what the abstract type *X* is.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This gives flexibility for choosing types suited to a particular implementation, while clients that use only values of the interface type—the existential type—are isolated from these choices.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In general it's impossible for the typechecker to infer which existential type a given module belongs to.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In the above example intT { a: int; f: (int → int); } could also have the type ∃X { a: X; f: (X → int); }.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Although abstract data types and modules had been implemented in programming languages for quite some time, it wasn't until 1988 that John C.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Mitchell and Gordon Plotkin established the formal theory under the slogan: "Abstract [data] types have existential type".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The theory is a second-order typed lambda calculus similar to System F, but with existential instead of universal quantification.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In a type system with Gradual typing, variables may be assigned a type either at compile-time (which is static typing), or at runtime (which is dynamic typing).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This allows software developers to choose either type paradigm as appropriate, from within a single language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Gradual typing uses a special type named *dynamic* to represent statically unknown types; gradual typing replaces the notion of type equality with a new relation called *consistency* that relates the dynamic type to every other type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The consistency relation is symmetric but not transitive.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Many static type systems, such as those of C and Java, require *type declarations*: the programmer must explicitly associate each variable with a specific type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Others, such as Haskell's, perform *type inference*: the compiler draws conclusions about the types of variables based on how programmers use those variables.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, given a function `f(x, y)` that adds `x` and `y` together, the compiler can infer that `x` and `y` must be numbers—since addition is only defined for numbers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Thus, any call to `f` elsewhere in the program that specifies a non-numeric type (such as a string or list) as an argument would signal an error.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Numerical and string constants and expressions in code can and often do imply type in a particular context.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, an expression `3.14` might imply a type of floating-point, while `[1, 2, 3]` might imply a list of integers—typically an array.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Type inference is in general possible, if it is computable in the type system in question.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Moreover, even if inference is not computable in general for a given type system, inference is often possible for a large subset of real-world programs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Haskell's type system, a version of Hindley–Milner, is a restriction of System Fω to so-called rank-1 polymorphic types, in which type inference is computable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Most Haskell compilers allow arbitrary-rank polymorphism as an extension, but this makes type inference not computable.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A type system that assigns types to terms in type environments using typing rules is naturally associated with the decision problems of type checking, typability, and type inhabitation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Some languages like C# or Scala have a unified type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This means that all C# types including primitive types inherit from a single root object.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Every type in C# inherits from the Object class.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Some languages, like Java and Raku, have a root type but also have primitive types that are not objects.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Java provides wrapper object types that exist together with the primitive types so developers can use either the wrapper object types or the simpler non-object primitive types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Raku automatically converts primitive types to objects when their methods are accessed.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] A type checker for a statically typed language must verify that the type of any expression is consistent with the type expected by the context in which that expression appears.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] For example, in an assignment statement of the form `x := *e*`, the inferred type of the expression *`e`* must be consistent with the declared or inferred type of the variable `x`.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] This notion of consistency, called *compatibility*, is specific to each programming language.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] If the type of *`e`* and the type of `x` are the same, and assignment is allowed for that type, then this is a valid expression.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Thus, in the simplest type systems, the question of whether two types are compatible reduces to that of whether they are *equal* (or *equivalent*).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Different languages, however, have different criteria for when two type expressions are understood to denote the same type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] In languages with subtyping, the compatibility relation is more complex: If `B` is a subtype of `A`, then a value of type `B` can be used in a context where one of type `A` is expected (covariant), even if the reverse is not true.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] Like equivalence, the subtype relation is defined differently for each programming language, with many variations possible.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-system] The presence of parametric or ad hoc polymorphism in a language may also have implications for type compatibility.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In mathematical logic, and theoretical computer science, **type theory** is the study of formal systems that classify expressions or mathematical objects by their *types*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Roughly speaking, a type plays a similar role to that played by a data type in programming: it specifies what kind of thing an expression is and how it may be used.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theories are used in the study of programming languages (type systems), formal logic, and the formalization of mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Some type theories have been proposed as alternatives to set theory as a foundation of mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Examples include Alonzo Church's simple theory of types and Per Martin-Löf's intuitionistic type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Many proof assistants are based on type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] For example, the underlying formal language of Rocq (formerly Coq) is the calculus of inductive constructions, while Lean is based on dependent type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theory was created to avoid paradoxes in naive set theory and formal logic, such as Russell's paradox which demonstrates that, without proper axioms, it is possible to define the set of all sets that are not members of themselves; this set both contains itself and does not contain itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Between 1902 and 1908, Bertrand Russell proposed various solutions to this problem.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] By 1908, Russell arrived at a ramified theory of types together with an axiom of reducibility, both of which appeared in Whitehead and Russell's *Principia Mathematica* published in 1910, 1912, and 1913.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] This system avoided contradictions suggested in Russell's paradox by creating a hierarchy of types and then assigning each concrete mathematical entity to a specific type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Entities of a given type were built exclusively of subtypes of that type, thus preventing an entity from being defined using itself.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] This resolution of Russell's paradox is similar to approaches taken in other formal systems, such as Zermelo-Fraenkel set theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theory is particularly popular in conjunction with Alonzo Church's lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] One notable early example of type theory is Church's simply typed lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Church's theory of types helped the formal system avoid the Kleene–Rosser paradox that afflicted the original untyped lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Church demonstrated that it could serve as a foundation of mathematics and it was referred to as a higher-order logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In the modern literature, "type theory" refers to a typed system based around lambda calculus.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] One influential system is Per Martin-Löf's intuitionistic type theory, which was proposed as a foundation for constructive mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Another is Thierry Coquand's calculus of constructions, which is used as the foundation by Rocq (previously known as *Coq*), Lean, and other computer proof assistants.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theory is an active area of research, one direction being the development of homotopy type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The first computer proof assistant, called Automath, used type theory to encode mathematics on a computer.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Martin-Löf specifically developed intuitionistic type theory to encode *all* mathematics to serve as a new foundation for mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] There is ongoing research into mathematical foundations using homotopy type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Mathematicians working in category theory already had difficulty working with the widely accepted foundation of Zermelo–Fraenkel set theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] This led to proposals such as Lawvere's Elementary Theory of the Category of Sets (ETCS).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Homotopy type theory continues in this line using type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Researchers are exploring connections between dependent types (especially the identity type) and algebraic topology (specifically homotopy).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Much of the current research into type theory is driven by proof checkers, interactive proof assistants, and automated theorem provers.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Many type theories are supported by LEGO and Isabelle.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Isabelle also supports foundations besides type theories, such as ZFC.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Mizar is an example of a proof system that only supports set theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Any static program analysis, such as the type checking algorithms in the semantic analysis phase of compiler, has a connection to type theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A prime example is Agda, a programming language which uses UTT (Luo's Unified Theory of dependent Types) for its type system.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The programming language ML was developed for manipulating type theories (see *Logic for Computable Functions*) and its own type system was heavily influenced by them.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theory is also widely used in formal theories of semantics of natural languages, especially Montague grammar and its descendants.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In particular, categorial grammars and pregroup grammars extensively use type constructors to define the types (*noun*, *verb*, etc.) of words.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A complex type ⟨ a , b ⟩ {\displaystyle \langle a,b\rangle } ({\displaystyle \langle a,b\rangle }) is the type of functions from entities of type a {\displaystyle a} ({\displaystyle a}) to entities of type ⁠ b {\displaystyle b} ({\displaystyle b})⁠.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Thus one has types like ⟨ e , t ⟩ {\displaystyle \langle e,t\rangle } ({\displaystyle \langle e,t\rangle }) that are interpreted as elements of the set of functions from entities to truth-values, i.e. indicator functions of sets of entities.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] An expression of type ⟨ ⟨ e , t ⟩ , t ⟩ {\displaystyle \langle \langle e,t\rangle ,t\rangle } ({\displaystyle \langle \langle e,t\rangle ,t\rangle }) is a function from sets of entities to truth-values, i.e. a (indicator function of a) set of sets.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] This latter type is standardly taken to be the type of natural language quantifiers, like *everybody* or *nobody* (Montague 1973, Barwise and Cooper 1981).
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theory with records is a formal semantics representation framework, using *records* to express *type theory types*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] It has been used in natural language processing, principally computational semantics and dialogue systems.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Gregory Bateson introduced a theory of logical types into the social sciences; his notions of double bind and logical levels are based on Russell's theory of types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A type theory is a mathematical logic, which is to say it is a collection of rules of inference that result in judgments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Most logics have judgments asserting "The proposition φ {\displaystyle \varphi } ({\displaystyle \varphi }) is true", or "The formula φ {\displaystyle \varphi } ({\displaystyle \varphi }) is a well-formed formula".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A type theory has judgments that define types and assign them to a collection of formal objects, known as terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A term and its type are often written together as ⁠ t e r m : t y p e {\displaystyle \mathrm {term} :{\mathsf {type}}} ({\displaystyle \mathrm {term} :{\mathsf {type}}})⁠.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A term in logic is recursively defined as a constant symbol, variable, or a function application, where a term is applied to another term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Such judgments are formally written with the turnstile symbol ⁠ ⊢ {\displaystyle \vdash } ({\displaystyle \vdash })⁠.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] If there are no assumptions, there will be nothing to the left of the turnstile.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The list of assumptions on the left is the *context* of the judgment.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Capital greek letters, such as Γ {\displaystyle \Gamma } ({\displaystyle \Gamma }) and Δ {\displaystyle \Delta } ({\displaystyle \Delta }), are common choices to represent some or all of the assumptions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The 4 different judgments are thus usually written as follows.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Some textbooks use a triple equal sign ≡ {\displaystyle \equiv } ({\displaystyle \equiv }) to stress that this is judgmental equality and thus an extrinsic notion of equality.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The judgments enforce that every term has a type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The type will restrict which rules can be applied to a term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A type theory's inference rules say what judgments can be made, based on the existence of other judgments.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Rules are expressed as a Gentzen-style deduction using a horizontal line, with the required input judgments above the line and the resulting judgment below the line.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] To generate a particular judgment in type theory, there must be a rule to generate it, as well as rules to generate all of that rule's required inputs, and so on.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The applied rules form a proof tree, where the top-most rules need no assumptions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] One example of a rule that does not require any inputs is one that states the type of a constant term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Generally, the desired conclusion of a proof in type theory is one of type inhabitation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Girard's paradox shows that type inhabitation is strongly related to the consistency of a type system with Curry–Howard correspondence.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] To be sound, such a system must have uninhabited types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] For examples of rules, an interested reader may follow Appendix A.2 of the *Homotopy Type Theory* book, or read Martin-Löf's Intuitionistic Type Theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The logical framework of a type theory bears a resemblance to intuitionistic, or constructive, logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Formally, type theory is often cited as an implementation of the Brouwer–Heyting–Kolmogorov interpretation of intuitionistic logic.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Additionally, connections can be made to category theory and computer programs.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] When used as a foundation, certain types are interpreted to be propositions (statements that can be proven), and terms inhabiting the type are interpreted to be proofs of that proposition.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] When some types are interpreted as propositions, there is a set of common types that can be used to connect them to make a Boolean algebra out of types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] However, the logic is not classical logic but intuitionistic logic, which is to say it does not have the law of excluded middle nor double negation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Because the law of excluded middle does not hold, there is no term of type ⁠ Π A .
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Likewise, double negation does not hold, so there is no term of type ⁠ Π A .
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] It is possible to include the law of excluded middle and double negation into a type theory, by rule or assumption.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] However, terms may not compute down to canonical terms and it will interfere with the ability to determine if two terms are judgementally equal to each other.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Per Martin-Löf proposed his intuitionistic type theory as a foundation for constructive mathematics.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In type theory, existence is accomplished using the dependent product type, and its proof requires a term of that type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] An example of a non-constructive proof is proof by contradiction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The first step is assuming that x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) does not exist and refuting it by contradiction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The conclusion from that step is "it is not the case that x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) does not exist".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The last step is, by double negation, concluding that x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) exists.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Constructive mathematics does not allow the last step of removing the double negation to conclude that x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) exists.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Most of the type theories proposed as foundations are constructive, and this includes most of the ones used by proof assistants.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] It is possible to add non-constructive features to a type theory, by rule or assumption.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] These include operators on continuations such as call with current continuation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] However, these operators tend to break desirable properties such as canonicity and parametricity.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The Curry–Howard correspondence is the observed similarity between logics and programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The implication in logic, "A → {\displaystyle \to } ({\displaystyle \to }) B" resembles a function from type "A" to type "B".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] For a variety of logics, the rules are similar to expressions in a programming language's types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The similarity goes farther, as applications of the rules resemble programs in the programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Thus, the correspondence is often summarized as "proofs as programs".
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The opposition of terms and types can also be viewed as one of *implementation* and *specification*.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] By program synthesis, (the computational counterpart of) type inhabitation can be used to construct (all or parts of) programs from the specification given in the form of type information.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Many programs that work with type theory (e.g., interactive theorem provers) also do type inferencing.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] It lets them select the rules that the user intends, with fewer actions by the user.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Although the initial motivation for category theory was far removed from foundationalism, the two fields turned out to have deep connections.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The interplay, known as categorical logic, has been a subject of active research since then; see the monograph of Jacobs (1999) for instance.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Homotopy type theory attempts to combine type theory and category theory.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] It focuses on equalities, especially equalities between types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Homotopy type theory differs from intuitionistic type theory mostly by its handling of the equality type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In 2016, cubical type theory was proposed, which is a homotopy type theory with normalization.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The most basic types are called atoms, and a term whose type is an atom is known as an atomic term.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] For example, the following may be atomic terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In addition to atomic terms, most modern type theories also allow for functions.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Types of this form are known as *simple* types.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Some terms may be declared directly as having a simple type, such as the following term, ⁠ a d d {\displaystyle \mathrm {add} } ({\displaystyle \mathrm {add} })⁠, which takes in two natural numbers in sequence and returns one natural number.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The convention is that the arrow is right associative, so the parentheses may be dropped from ⁠ a d d {\displaystyle \mathrm {add} } ({\displaystyle \mathrm {add} })⁠'s type.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] New function terms may be constructed using lambda expressions, and are called lambda terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The following lambda term represents a function which doubles an input natural number.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The variable is x {\displaystyle x} ({\displaystyle x}) and (implicit from the lambda term's type) must have type ⁠ n a t {\displaystyle {\mathsf {nat}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathsf {nat}}})⁠.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The term a d d x x {\displaystyle \mathrm {add} \,x\,x} ({\displaystyle \mathrm {add} \,x\,x}) has type ⁠ n a t {\displaystyle {\mathsf {nat}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathsf {nat}}})⁠, which is seen by applying the function application inference rule twice.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Thus, the lambda term has type n a t → n a t {\displaystyle {\mathsf {nat}}\to {\mathsf {nat}}} ({\displaystyle {\mathsf {nat}}\to {\mathsf {nat}}}), which means it is a function taking a natural number as an argument and returning a natural number.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] A lambda term is an anonymous function because it lacks a name.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The concept of anonymous functions appears in many programming languages.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The power of type theories is in specifying how terms may be combined by way of inference rules.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Parentheses indicate the order of operations; however, by convention, function application is left associative, so parentheses can be dropped where appropriate.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Type theories that allow for lambda terms also include inference rules known as β {\displaystyle \beta } ({\displaystyle \beta })-reduction and η {\displaystyle \eta } ({\displaystyle \eta })-reduction.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] They generalize the notion of function application to lambda terms.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] Therefore, the lambda expression is equivalent to just ⁠ t {\displaystyle t} ({\displaystyle t})⁠, as both take in one argument and apply t {\displaystyle t} ({\displaystyle t}) to it.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] For example, the following term may be β {\displaystyle \beta } ({\displaystyle \beta })-reduced.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] In type theories that also establish notions of equality for types and terms, there are corresponding inference rules of β {\displaystyle \beta } ({\displaystyle \beta })-equality and η {\displaystyle \eta } ({\displaystyle \eta })-equality.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] The type is usually written ⊥ {\displaystyle \bot } ({\displaystyle \bot }) or ⁠ 0 {\displaystyle \mathbb {0} } ({\displaystyle \mathbb {0} })⁠.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] One use for the empty type is proofs of type inhabitation.
[src:lambda-type-theory/type-theory-p01] If for a type ⁠ a {\displaystyle a} ({\displaystyle a})⁠, it is consistent to derive a function of type ⁠ a → ⊥ {\displaystyle a\to \bot } ({\displaystyle a\to \bot })⁠, then a {\displaystyle a} ({\displaystyle a}) is *uninhabited*, which is to say it has no terms.
